It has no <a href=\"/wiki/Natural_satellite\">natural satellite</a>. It is named after the <a href=\"/wiki/Venus_(mythology)\">Roman goddess of love and beauty</a>. It is the second-brightest natural object in the night sky after the <a href=\"/wiki/Moon\">Moon</a>, reaching an <a href=\"/wiki/Apparent_magnitude\">apparent magnitude</a> of 4.6, bright enough to cast shadows.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-15\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 14;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[14]</span></a></span> Because Venus is an <a href=\"/wiki/Inferior_and_superior_planets\">inferior planet</a> from Earth, it never appears to venture far from the Sun; its <a href=\"/wiki/Elongation_(astronomy)\">elongation</a> reaches a maximum of 47.8.</p></span><div class=\"hatnote\">This article is about the planet. 05-23 18:38:40.838 debug OkHttp " list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<ol class=\"mw-references\" data-mw-group=\"note\"><li id=\"cite_note-8\"> <span class=\"mw-reference-text\">Defining the rotation as retrograde, as done by NASA space missions and the USGS, puts <a href=\"/wiki/Ishtar_Terra\">Ishtar Terra</a> in the northern hemisphere and makes the axial tilt 2.64. Following the <a href=\"/wiki/Right-hand_rule\">right-hand rule</a> for prograde rotation puts Ishtar Terra in the southern hemisphere and makes the axial tilt 177.36.</span></li></ol></div></td></tr></tbody></table>\n\n\n\n<p>Venus is a <a href=\"/wiki/Terrestrial_planet\">terrestrial planet</a> and is sometimes called Earth's \"sister planet\" because of their similar size, mass, proximity to the Sun, and bulk composition. It is radically different from Earth in other respects. It has the densest <a href=\"/wiki/Atmosphere\">atmosphere</a> of the four terrestrial planets, consisting of more than 96% <a href=\"/wiki/Carbon_dioxide\">carbon dioxide</a>. The <a href=\"/wiki/Atmospheric_pressure\">atmospheric pressure</a> at the planet's surface is 92 times that of Earth. Venus is by far the hottest planet in the Solar System, with a mean surface temperature of <span>735</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span>K (462</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span>C; 863</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span>F)</span>, even though <a href=\"/wiki/Mercury_(planet)\">Mercury</a> is closer to the Sun. Venus is shrouded by an opaque layer of highly reflective clouds of <a href=\"/wiki/Sulfuric_acid\">sulfuric acid</a>, preventing its surface from being seen from space in <a href=\"/wiki/Visible_light\">visible light</a>. It may have had water oceans in the past,<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-16\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 15;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[15]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-17\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 16;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[16]</span></a></span> but these would have vaporised as the temperature rose due to a <a href=\"/wiki/Runaway_greenhouse_effect\">runaway greenhouse effect</a>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Jakosky-18\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 17;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[17]</span></a></span> The water has probably <a href=\"/wiki/Photodissociation\">photodissociated</a>, and the free hydrogen has been <a href=\"/wiki/Atmospheric_escape\">swept into interplanetary space</a> by the <a href=\"/wiki/Solar_wind\">solar wind</a> because of the lack of a <a href=\"/wiki/Magnetosphere\">planetary magnetic field</a>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-solarwind-19\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 18;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[18]</span></a></span> Venus's surface is a dry desertscape interspersed with slab-like rocks and periodically resurfaced by <a href=\"/wiki/Volcanology_of_Venus\">volcanism</a>.</p>\n\n<p>As one of the brightest objects in the sky, Venus has been a major fixture in human culture for as long as records have existed. It has been made sacred to gods of many cultures, and has been a prime inspiration for writers and poets as the \"morning star\" and \"evening star\". Venus was the first planet to have its motions plotted across the sky, as early as the second millennium BC,<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-practice-20\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 19;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[19]</span></a></span> and was a prime target for early interplanetary exploration as the closest planet to Earth. It was the first planet beyond Earth visited by a spacecraft (<a href=\"/wiki/Mariner_2\">Mariner 2</a>) in 1962, and the first to be successfully landed on (by <a href=\"/wiki/Venera_7\">Venera 7</a>) in 1970. Venus's thick clouds render observation of its surface impossible in visible light, and the first detailed maps did not emerge until the arrival of the <a href=\"/wiki/Magellan_(spacecraft)\">Magellan orbiter</a> in 1991. Plans have been proposed for <a href=\"/wiki/Rover_(
05-23 18:38:40.838 debug OkHttp space_exploration)\">rovers</a> or more complex missions, but they are hindered by Venus's hostile surface conditions.</p>\n\n"},{"id":1,"toclevel":1,"anchor":"Physical_characteristics","line":"Physical characteristics"},{"id":2,"toclevel":2,"anchor":"Geography","line":"Geography"},{"id":3,"toclevel":2,"anchor":"Surface_geology","line":"Surface geology"},{"id":4,"toclevel":2,"anchor":"Internal_structure","line":"Internal structure"},{"id":5,"toclevel":2,"anchor":"Atmosphere_and_climate","line":"Atmosphere and climate"},{"id":6,"toclevel":2,"anchor":"Magnetic_field_and_core","line":"Magnetic field and core"},{"id":7,"toclevel":1,"anchor":"Orbit_and_rotation","line":"Orbit and rotation"},{"id":8,"toclevel":1,"anchor":"Observation","line":"Observation"},{"id":9,"toclevel":2,"anchor":"Transits","line":"Transits"},{"id":10,"toclevel":2,"anchor":"Pentagram_of_Venus","line":"Pentagram of Venus"},{"id":11,"toclevel":2,"anchor":"Ashen_light","line":"Ashen light"},{"id":12,"toclevel":1,"anchor":"Studies","line":"Studies"},{"id":13,"toclevel":2,"anchor":"Early_studies","line":"Early studies"},{"id":14,"toclevel":2,"anchor":"Ground-based_research","line":"Ground-based research"},{"id":15,"toclevel":2,"anchor":"Exploration","line":"Exploration"},{"id":16,"toclevel":1,"anchor":"In_culture","line":"In culture"},{"id":17,"toclevel":2,"anchor":"Etymology","line":"Etymology"},{"id":18,"toclevel":2,"anchor":"Symbol","line":"Symbol"},{"id":19,"toclevel":2,"anchor":"In_fiction","line":"In fiction"},{"id":20,"toclevel":1,"anchor":"Colonisation_and_terraforming","line":"Colonisation and terraforming"},{"id":21,"toclevel":1,"anchor":"See_also","line":"See also"},{"id":22,"toclevel":1,"anchor":"Notes","line":"Notes"},{"id":23,"toclevel":1,"anchor":"References","line":"References"},{"id":24,"toclevel":1,"anchor":"External_links","line":"External links"},{"id":25,"toclevel":2,"anchor":"Cartographic_resources","line":"Cartographic resources"}]}

05-23 18:38:41.418 debug OkHttp {"sections":[{"id":1,"text":"\n<figure class=\"mw-default-size mw-halign-left\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Venus,_Earth_size_comparison.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/92/Venus%2C_Earth_size_comparison.jpg/220px-Venus%2C_Earth_size_comparison.jpg\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/92/Venus%2C_Earth_size_comparison.jpg/440px-Venus%2C_Earth_size_comparison.jpg 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/92/Venus%2C_Earth_size_comparison.jpg/330px-Venus%2C_Earth_size_comparison.jpg 1.5x\" height=\"114\" width=\"220\"></a><figcaption>Size comparison with <a href=\"/wiki/Earth\" class=\"image\">Earth</a></figcaption></figure>\n<p>Venus is one of the four <a href=\"/wiki/Terrestrial_planet\">terrestrial planets</a> in the Solar System, meaning that it is a rocky body like Earth. It is similar to Earth in size and mass, and is often described as Earth's \"sister\" or \"twin\".<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-21\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 20;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[20]</span></a></span> The diameter of Venus is 12,092<span>&nbsp;</span>km (only 650<span>&nbsp;</span>km less than Earth's) and its mass is 81.5% of Earth's. Conditions on the Venusian surface differ radically from those on Earth because of its dense <a href=\"/wiki/Carbon_dioxide\">carbon dioxide</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Atmosphere\">atmosphere</a>. The mass of the atmosphere of Venus is 96.5% carbon dioxide, with most of the remaining 3.5% being <a href=\"/wiki/Nitrogen\">nitrogen</a>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-22\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 21;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[21]</span></a></span></p>\n\n","toclevel":1,"line":"Physical characteristics","anchor":"Physical_characteristics"},{"id":2,"text":"\n<p>The Venusian surface was a subject of speculation until some of its secrets were revealed by <a href=\"/wiki/Planetary_science\">planetary science</a> in the 20th century. <a href=\"/wiki/Venera\">Venera</a> landers in 1975 and 1982 returned images of a surface covered in sediment and relatively angular rocks.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-23\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 22;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[22]</span></a></span> The surface was mapped in detail by <a href=\"/wiki/Magellan_(spacecraft)\"><i>Magellan</i></a> in 199091. The ground shows evidence of extensive <a href=\"/wiki/Volcanology_of_Venus\">volcanism</a>, and the <a href=\"/wiki/Sulfur\">sulfur</a> in the atmosphere may indicate that there have been some recent eruptions.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-24\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 23;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[23]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-25\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 24;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[24]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>About 80% of the Venusian surface is covered by smooth, volcanic plains, consisting of 70% plains with wrinkle ridges and 10% smooth or lobate plains.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-26\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 25;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[25]</span></a></span> Two <a href=\"/wiki/Highland_continent\">highland \"continents\"</a> make up the rest of its surface area, one lying in the planet's northern hemisphere and the other just south of the equator. The northern continent is called <a href=\"/wiki/Ishtar_Terra\">Ishtar Terra</a>, after <a href=\"/wiki/Ishtar\">Ishtar</a> the <a href=\"/wiki/Babylon\">Babylonian</a> goddess of love, and is about the size of Australia. <a href=\"/wiki/Maxwell_Montes\">Maxwell Montes</a>, the highest mountain on Venus, lies on Ishtar Terra. Its peak is 11<span>&nbsp;</span>km above the Venusian average surface elevation. The southern continent is called <a href=\"/wiki/Aphrodite_Terra\">Aphrodite Terra</a>, after the <a href=\"/wiki/Greek_mythology\">Greek</a> goddess of love, and is the larger of the two highland regions at roughly the size of
05-23 18:38:41.418 debug OkHttp South America. A network of fractures and faults covers much of this area.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Kaufmann-27\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 26;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[26]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>The absence of evidence of <a href=\"/wiki/Lava\">lava</a> flow accompanying any of the visible <a href=\"/wiki/Caldera\">caldera</a> remains an enigma. The planet has few <a href=\"/wiki/Impact_crater\">impact craters</a>, demonstrating that the surface is relatively young, approximately 300600 million years old.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Nimmo98-28\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 27;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[27]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Strom1994-29\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 28;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[28]</span></a></span> Venus has some unique surface features in addition to the impact craters, mountains, and valleys commonly found on rocky planets. Among these are flat-topped volcanic features called \"<a href=\"/wiki/Farra_(Venus)\">farra</a>\", which look somewhat like pancakes and range in size from 20 to 50<span>&nbsp;</span>km across, and from 100 to 1,000<span>&nbsp;</span>m high; radial, star-like fracture systems called \"novae\"; features with both radial and concentric fractures resembling spider webs, known as \"<a href=\"/wiki/Arachnoid_(astrogeology)\">arachnoids</a>\"; and \"coronae\", circular rings of fractures sometimes surrounded by a depression. These features are volcanic in origin.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Frankel-30\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 29;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[29]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>Most Venusian surface features are named after historical and mythological women.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-31\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 30;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[30]</span></a></span> Exceptions are Maxwell Montes, named after <a href=\"/wiki/James_Clerk_Maxwell\">James Clerk Maxwell</a>, and highland regions <a href=\"/wiki/Alpha_Regio\">Alpha Regio</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Beta_Regio\">Beta Regio</a>, and <a href=\"/wiki/Ovda_Regio\">Ovda Regio</a>. The latter three features were named before the current system was adopted by the <a href=\"/wiki/International_Astronomical_Union\">International Astronomical Union</a>, the body which oversees <a href=\"/wiki/Planetary_nomenclature\">planetary nomenclature</a>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-jpl-magellan-32\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 31;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[31]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>The longitudes of physical features on Venus are expressed relative to its <a href=\"/wiki/Prime_meridian\">prime meridian</a>. The original prime meridian passed through the radar-bright spot at the centre of the oval feature Eve, located south of Alpha Regio.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Davies_1994-33\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 32;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[32]</span></a></span> After the Venera missions were completed, the prime meridian was redefined to pass through the central peak in the crater Ariadne.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-34\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 33;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[33]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-jpl-magellan2-35\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 34;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[34]</span></a></span></p>\n\n","toclevel":2,"line":"Geography","anchor":"Geography"},{"id":3,"text":"\n<div class=\"hatnote relarticle mainarticle\">Main articles: <a href=\"/wiki/Geology_of_Venus\">Geology of Venus</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Volcanology_of_Venus\">Volcanology of Venus</a></div>\n<figure class=\"mw-default-size\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Maat_Mons_on_Venus.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/16/Maat_Mons_on_Venus.jpg/220px-Maat_Mons_on_Venus.jpg\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/16/Maa

Venus has several times as many volcanoes as Earth, and it has 167 large volcanoes that are over 100<span>&nbsp;</span>km across. The only volcanic complex of this size on Earth is the <a href=\"/wiki/Hawaii_(island)\">Big Island</a> of Hawaii.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Frankel-30\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 29;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[29]</span></a></span><sup class=\"reference\" style=\"white-space:nowrap;\" about=\"#mwt105\" typeof=\"mw:Transclusion\" data-mw=\"{&quot;parts&quot;:[{&quot;template&quot;:{&quot;target&quot;:{&quot;wt&quot;:&quot;rp&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:&quot;./Template:Rp&quot;},&quot;params&quot;:{&quot;1&quot;:{&quot;wt&quot;:&quot;154&quot;}},&quot;i&quot;:0}}]}\" id=\"mwZg\">:154</sup> This is not because Venus is more volcanically active than Earth, but because its crust is older. Earth's <a href=\"/wiki/Oceanic_crust\">oceanic crust</a> is continually recycled by <a href=\"/wiki/Subduction\">subduction</a> at the boundaries of <a href=\"/wiki/Tectonic_plate\">tectonic plates</a>, and has an average age of about 100 million years,<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-36\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 35;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[35]</span></a></span> whereas the Venusian surface is estimated to be 300600 million years old.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Nimmo98-28\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 27;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[27]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Frankel-30\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 29;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[29]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>Several lines of evidence point to ongoing <a href=\"/wiki/Volcano\">volcanic</a> activity on Venus. During the Soviet <a href=\"/wiki/Venera_programme\">Venera programme</a>, the <i><a href=\"/wiki/Venera_9\">Venera 9</a></i> orbiter obtained spectroscopic evidence of <a href=\"/wiki/Lightning\">lightning</a> on Venus,<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-37\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 36;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[36]</span></a></span> and the <i><a href=\"/wiki/Venera_12\">Venera 12</a></i> descent probe obtained additional evidence of lightning and <a href=\"/wiki/Thunder\">thunder</a>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Russell.2C_Philips-38\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 37;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[37]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-39\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 38;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[38]</span></a></span> The <a href=\"/wiki/European_Space_Agency\">European Space Agency</a>'s <i><a href=\"/wiki/Venus_Express\">Venus Express</a></i> in 2007 detected <a href=\"/wiki/Whistler_(radio)\">whistler waves</a> further confirming the occurrence of lightning on Venus.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Russell_2007-40\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 39;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[39]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Venus_Express-41\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 40;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[40]</span></a></span> Although rainfall drives <a href=\"/wiki/Thunderstorm\">thunderstorms</a> on Earth, there is no rainfall on the surface of Venus (though <a href=\"/wiki/Sulfuric_acid\">sulfuric acid</a> rain falls in the upper atmosphere, then evaporates around 25<span>&nbsp;</span>km above the surface). 05-23 18:38:48.548 debug OkHttp tyle=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 29;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[29]</span></a></span> Earth <a href=\"/wiki/Gravity\">gravitationally</a> interacts with other objects in space, especially the Sun and the <a href=\"/wiki/Moon\">Moon</a>. During one orbit around the Sun, Earth rotates about its own axis 366.26 times, creating 365.26 <a href=\"/wiki/Solar_time\">solar days</a> or one <a href=\"/wiki/Sidereal_year\">sidereal year</a>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-sidereal_solar-36\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 7;\" data-mw-group=\"n\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[n 7]</span></a></span> Earth's axis of rotation is tilted 23.4 away from the perpendicular of its <a href=\"/wiki/Orbital_plane_(astronomy)\">orbital plane</a>, producing seasonal variations on the planet's surface with a period of one <a href=\"/wiki/Tropical_year\">tropical year</a> (365.24 solar days).<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-yoder1995-37\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 30;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[30]</span></a></span> The Moon is Earth's only permanent <a href=\"/wiki/Natural_satellite\">natural satellite</a>. Its gravitational interaction with Earth causes ocean tides, stabilizes the orientation of Earth's rotational axis, and gradually slows Earth's rotational rate.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-aaa428_261-38\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 31;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[31]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>Earth's <a href=\"/wiki/Lithosphere\">lithosphere</a> is divided into several rigid <a href=\"/wiki/Plate_tectonics\">tectonic plates</a> that migrate across the surface over periods of many millions of years. 71% of Earth's surface is covered with water,<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-39\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 32;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[32]</span></a></span> with the remainder consisting of continents and islands that together have many lakes and other sources of water that contribute to the <a href=\"/wiki/Hydrosphere\">hydrosphere</a>. Earth's <a href=\"/wiki/Polar_regions_of_Earth\">polar regions</a> are mostly covered with ice, including the <a href=\"/wiki/Antarctic_ice_sheet\">Antarctic ice sheet</a> and the sea ice of the Arctic ice pack. Earth's interior remains active with a solid iron inner core, a liquid outer core that generates the magnetic field, and a convecting <a href=\"/wiki/Mantle_(geology)\">mantle</a> that drives plate tectonics.</p>\n\n<p>Within its first billion years,<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-age_earth1-40\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 33;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[33]</span></a></span> life appeared in Earth's oceans and began to affect <a href=\"/wiki/Atmosphere_of_Earth\">its atmosphere</a> and surface, leading to the proliferation of <a href=\"/wiki/Aerobic_organism\">aerobic</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Anaerobic_organism\">anaerobic organisms</a>. Since then, the combination of Earth's distance from the Sun, its physical properties and <a href=\"/wiki/Geological_history_of_Earth\">its geological history</a> have allowed life to thrive and evolve. The earliest undisputed life on Earth arose at least 3.5 billion years ago. Earlier physical evidence of life includes <a href=\"/wiki/Biogenic\">biogenic</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Graphite\">graphite</a> in 3.7 billion-year-old <a href=\"/wiki/Metasediment\">metasedimentary rocks</a> discovered in southwestern <a href=\"/wiki/Greenland\">Greenland</a>, as well as \"remains of <a href=\"/wiki/Biotic_material\">biotic life</a>\" found in 4.1 billion-year-old rocks in <a href=\"/wiki/Western_Australia\">Western Australia</a>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-AP-20151019-41\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 34;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[34]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-PNAS-20151014-pdf-42\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 35;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[35]</span></a></span> Earth's <a href=\"/wiki/Biodiversity\">biodi

This was followed a half billion years later by the <a href=\"/wiki/Last_universal_common_ancestor\">last common ancestor of all life</a>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-sa282_6_90-70\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 63;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[63]</span></a></span> The development of <a href=\"/wiki/Photosynthesis\">photosynthesis</a> allowed the Sun's energy to be harvested directly by life forms; the resultant <a href=\"/wiki/Molecular_oxygen\">molecular oxygen</a> (O<sub id=\"mweQ\">2</sub>) accumulated in the atmosphere and due to interaction with ultraviolet solar radiation, formed a protective <a href=\"/wiki/Ozone_layer\">ozone layer</a> (O<sub id=\"mwew\">3</sub>) in the upper atmosphere.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-NYT-20131003-71\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 64;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[64]</span></a></span> The incorporation of smaller cells within larger ones resulted in the <a href=\"/wiki/Endosymbiotic_theory\">development of complex cells</a> called <a href=\"/wiki/Eukaryotes\">eukaryotes</a>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-jas22_3_225-72\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 65;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[65]</span></a></span> True multicellular organisms formed as cells within <a href=\"/wiki/Colony_(biology)\">colonies</a> became increasingly specialized. Aided by the absorption of harmful <a href=\"/wiki/Ultraviolet_radiation\">ultraviolet radiation</a> by the ozone layer, life colonized Earth's surface.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-burton20021129-73\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 66;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[66]</span></a></span> The earliest <a href=\"/wiki/Fossil\">fossil</a> evidence for <a href=\"/wiki/Life\">life</a> is <a href=\"/wiki/Microbial_mat\">microbial mat</a> fossils found in 3.48 billion-year-old <a href=\"/wiki/Sandstone\">sandstone</a> in <a href=\"/wiki/Western_Australia\">Western Australia</a>,<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Origin1-74\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 67;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[67]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Origin2-75\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 68;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[68]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-RavenJohnson2002-76\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 69;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[69]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-AP-20131113-77\" style=\"coun

As a result of the steady accumulation of helium at the Sun's core, the <a href=\"/wiki/Solar_luminosity\">Sun's total luminosity</a> will slowly increase. The luminosity of the Sun will grow by 10% over the next <span class=\"nowrap\"><span style=\"display:none\" class=\"sortkey\">7016347133600000000</span>1.1<span>&nbsp;</span>Ga</span> and by 40% over the next <span class=\"nowrap\"><span style=\"display:none\" class=\"sortkey\">7017110451600000000</span>3.5<span>&nbsp;</span>Ga</span>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-sun_future-87\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 80;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[80]</span></a></span> Climate models indicate that the rise in radiation reaching Earth is likely to have dire consequences, including the loss of the oceans.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-icarus74_472-88\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 81;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[81]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>Earth's increasing surface temperature will accelerate the <a href=\"/wiki/Inorganic\">inorganic</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Carbon_cycle\">CO<sub 500<span class=\"nowrap\"><span style=\"display:none\" class=\"sortkey\">7016284018400000000</span>900<span>&nbsp;</span>Ma</span>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-britt2000-84\" Half of that land area is desert (14%),<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-hessd4_439-223\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 202;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[202]</span></a></span> high mountains (27%),<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-biodiv-224\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 203;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[203]</span></a></span> or other unsuitable terrain. The northernmost permanent settlement in the world is <a href=\"/wiki/Alert,_Nunavut\">Alert</a>, on <a href=\"/wiki/Ellesmere_Island\">Ellesmere Island</a> in <a href=\"/wiki/Nunavut\">Nunavut</a>, Canada.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-cfsa2006-225\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 204;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[204]</span></a></span> (8228N) The southernmost is the <a href=\"/wiki/AmundsenScott_South_Pole_Station\">AmundsenScott South Pole Station</a>, in Antarctica, almost exactly at the South Pole. (90S)</p>\n\n<p>Independent sovereign nations claim the planet's entire land surface, except for some parts of Antarctica, a few <a href=\"/wiki/CroatiaSerbia_border_dispute\">land parcels along the Danube</a> river's western bank, and the odd <a href=\"/wiki/Terra_nullius\">unclaimed area</a> of <a href=\"/wiki/Bir_Tawil\">Bir Tawil</a> between Egypt and Sudan. <span>As of 2015</span>, there are 193 <a href=\"/wiki/List_of_sovereign_states\">sovereign states</a> that are <a href=\"/wiki/Member_states_of_the_United_Nations\">member states of the United Nations</a>, plus two <a href=\"/wiki/United_Nations_General_Assembly_observers\">observer states</a> and 72 <a href=\"/wiki/Dependent_territory\">dependent territories</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/List_of_states_with_limited_recognition\">states with limited recognition</a>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-cia-17\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 14;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[14]</span></a></span> Historically, Earth has never had a <a href=\"/wiki/Sovereignty\">sovereign</a> government with authority over the entire globe although a number of nation-states have striven for <a href=\"/wiki/Hyperpower\">world domination</a> and failed.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-kennedy1989-226\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 205;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[205]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>The <a href=\"/wiki/United_Nations\">United Nations</a> is a worldwide <a href=\"/wiki/International_organization\">intergovernmental organization</a> that was created with the goal of intervening in the disputes between nations, thereby avoiding armed conflict.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-uncharter-227\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 206;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[206]</span></a></span> The U.N. serves primarily as a forum for international diplomacy and <a href=\"/wiki/International_law\">international law</a>. When the consensus of the membership permits, it provides a mechanism for armed intervention.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-un_int_law-228\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 207;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[207]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>The first human to orbit Earth was <a href=\"/wiki/Yuri_Gagarin\">Yuri Gagarin</a> on 12 April 1961.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-kuhn2006-229\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 208;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[208]</span></a></span> In total, about 48

Mars is the site of <a href=\"/wiki/Olympus_Mons\">Olympus Mons</a>, the largest <a href=\"/wiki/Volcano\">volcano</a> and second-highest known mountain in the Solar System, and of <a href=\"/wiki/Valles_Marineris\">Valles Marineris</a>, one of the largest canyons in the Solar System. The smooth <a href=\"/wiki/Borealis_basin\">Borealis basin</a> in the northern hemisphere covers 40% of the planet and may be a giant impact feature.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-northcratersn-17\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 16;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[16]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-northcraterguard-18\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 17;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[17]</span></a></span> Mars has two <a href=\"/wiki/Moons_of_Mars\">moons</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Phobos_(moon)\">Phobos</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Deimos_(moon)\">Deimos</a>, which are small and irregularly shaped. These may be captured <a href=\"/wiki/Asteroid\">asteroids</a>,<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-19\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 18;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[18]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-adler-20\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 19;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[19]</span></a></span> similar to <a href=\"/wiki/5261_Eureka\">5261 Eureka</a>, a <a href=\"/wiki/Mars_trojan\">Mars trojan</a>.</p>\n\n<p>Until the first successful Mars flyby in 1965 by <i><a href=\"/wiki/Mariner_4\">Mariner 4</a></i>, many speculated about the presence of liquid water on the planet's surface. This was based on observed periodic variations in light and dark patches, particularly in the polar <a href=\"/wiki/Latitude\">latitudes</a>, which appeared to be seas and continents; long, dark <a href=\"/wiki/Striation_(geology)\">striations</a> were interpreted by some as irrigation channels for liquid water. These straight line features were later explained as <a href=\"/wiki/Optical_illusion\">optical illusions</a>, though geological evidence gathered by uncrewed missions suggests that Mars once had large-scale water coverage on its surface at some earlier stage of its existence.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-marswater-21\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 20;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[20]</span></a></span> In 2005, radar data revealed the presence of large quantities of water ice at the poles<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-specials1-22\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 21;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[21]</span></a></span> and at mid-latitudes.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-jsg.utexas.edu-23\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 22;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[22]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-esa050221-24\" style=\"counte

The <i><a href=\"/wiki/Phoenix_(spacecraft)\">Phoenix</a></i> lander directly sampled water ice in shallow Martian soil on July 31, 2008.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-spacecraft1-25\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 24;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[24]</span></a></span> On September 28, 2015, NASA announced the presence of briny flowing <a href=\"/wiki/Saline_water\">salt water</a> on the Martian surface.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-26\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 25;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[25]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>Mars is host to seven functioning <a href=\"/wiki/Spacecraft\">spacecraft</a>: five in orbit<i><a href=\"/wiki/2001_Mars_Odyssey\">2001 Mars Odyssey</a></i>, <i><a href=\"/wiki/Mars_Express\">Mars Express</a></i>, <i><a href=\"/wiki/Mars_Reconnaissance_Orbiter\">Mars Reconnaissance Orbiter</a></i>, <a href=\"/wiki/MAVEN\">MAVEN</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Mars_Orbiter_Mission\">Mars Orbiter Mission</a>and two on the surface<a href=\"/wiki/Mars_Exploration_Rover\">Mars Exploration Rover</a> <i><a href=\"/wiki/Opportunity_(rover)\">Opportunity</a></i> and the <a href=\"/wiki/Mars_Science_Laboratory\">Mars Science Laboratory</a> <i><a href=\"/wiki/Curiosity_(rover)\">Curiosity</a></i>. Observations by the <i><a href=\"/wiki/Mars_Reconnaissance_Orbiter\">Mars Reconnaissance Orbiter</a></i> have revealed possible flowing water during the warmest months on Mars.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-NASA_.E2.80.93_NASA_Spacecraft_Data_Suggest_Water_Flowing_on_Mars-27\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 26;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[26]</span></a></span> In 2013, NASA's <i>Curiosity</i> rover discovered that Mars's soil contains between 1.5% and 3% water by mass (albeit attached to other compounds and thus not freely accessible).<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Guardian-28\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 27;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[27]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>There are ongoing investigations assessing the past <a href=\"/wiki/Planetary_habitability\">habitability</a> potential of Mars, as well as <a href=\"/wiki/Life_on_Mars\">the possibility of extant life</a>. <i>In situ</i> investigations have been performed by the <a href=\"/wiki/Viking_program#Viking_landers\"><i>Viking</i> landers</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Spirit_(rover)\"><i>Spirit</i></a> and <i>Opportunity</i> rovers, <a href=\"/wiki/Phoenix_(spacecraft)\"><i>Phoenix</i></a> lander, and <i>Curiosity</i> rover. Besides silicon and oxygen, the most abundant elements in the Martian crust are iron, <a href=\"/wiki/Magnesium\">magnesium</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Aluminum\">aluminum</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Calcium\">calcium</a>, and <a href=\"/wiki/Potassium\">potassium</a>. The average thickness of the planet's crust is about <span>50</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span>km (31</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span>mi)</span>, with a maximum thickness of <span>125</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span>km (78</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span>mi)</span>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-jacque03-38\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 37;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[37]</span></a></span> Earth's crust, averaging <span>40</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span>km (25</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span>mi)</span>, is only one third as thick as Mars', relative to the sizes of the two planets.</p>\n\n","toclevel":2,"line":"Internal structure","anchor":"Internal_structure"},{"id":3,"text":"\n<div class=\"hatnote relarticle mainarticle\">Main article: <a href=\"/wiki/Geology_of_Mars\">Geology of Mars</a></div>\n\n<p>Mars is a <a href=\"/wiki/Terrestrial_planet\">terrestrial planet</a> that consists of minerals containing <a href=\"/wiki/Silicon\">silicon</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Oxygen\">oxygen</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Metal\">metals</a>, and other elements that typically make up <a href=\"/wiki/Rock_(geology)\">rock</a>. The surface of Mars is primarily composed of <a href=\"/wiki/Tholeiitic_magma_series\">tholeiitic</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Basalt\">basalt</a>,<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-science324_5928_736-39\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 38;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[38]</span></a></span> although parts are more <a href=\"/wiki/Silica\">silica</a>-rich than typical basalt and may be similar to <a href=\"/wiki/Andesitic\">andesitic</a> rocks on Earth or silica glass. Regions of low <a href=\"/wiki/Albedo\">albedo</a> show concentrations of <a href=\"/wiki/Plagioclase_feldspar\">plagioclase feldspar</a>, with northern low albedo regions displaying higher than normal concentrations of sheet silicates and high-silicon glass. Parts of the southern highlands include detectable amounts of high-calcium <a href=\"/wiki/Pyroxenes\">pyroxenes</a>. Localized concentrations of <a href=\"/wiki/Hematite\">hematite</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Olivine\">olivine</a> have also been found.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-jgr107_E6-40\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 39;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[39]</span></a></span> Much of the surface is deeply covered by finely grained <a href=\"/wiki/Iron(III)_oxide\">iron(III) oxide</a> dust.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-sci300a-41\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 40;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[40]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-sci300b-42\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 41;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[41]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<figure class=\"mw-default-size mw-halign-left\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:USGS-MarsMap-sim3292-20140714-crop.png\" class=\"im
05-23 18:38:57.848 debug OkHttp age\"><img src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1f/USGS-MarsMap-sim3292-20140714-crop.png/220px-USGS-MarsMap-sim3292-20140714-crop.png\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1f/USGS-MarsMap-sim3292-20140714-crop.png/440px-USGS-MarsMap-sim3292-20140714-crop.png 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1f/USGS-MarsMap-sim3292-20140714-crop.png/330px-USGS-MarsMap-sim3292-20140714-crop.png 1.5x\" height=\"248\" width=\"220\"></a><figcaption><a href=\"/wiki/Geology_of_Mars\" class=\"image\">Geologic map</a> of Mars (<a href=\"/wiki/USGS\" class=\"image\">USGS</a>, 2014)<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-USGS-20140714-43\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 42;\" class=\"image\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[42]</span></a></span></figcaption></figure>\n\n<p>Although Mars has no evidence of a current structured global <a href=\"/wiki/Magnetic_field\">magnetic field</a>,<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-magnetosphere-44\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 43;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[43]</span></a></span> observations show that parts of the planet's crust have been magnetized, and that alternating polarity reversals of its dipole field have occurred in the past. This <a href=\"/wiki/Paleomagnetism\">paleomagnetism</a> of magnetically susceptible minerals has properties that are similar to the <a href=\"/wiki/Magnetic_striping\">alternating bands found on the ocean floors of Earth</a>. One theory, published in 1999 and re-examined in October 2005 (with the help of the <i><a href=\"/wiki/Mars_Global_Surveyor\">Mars Global Surveyor</a></i>), is that these bands demonstrate <a href=\"/wiki/Plate_tectonics\">plate tectonics</a> on Mars four <a href=\"/wiki/1000000000_(number)\">billion</a> years ago, before the planetary <a href=\"/wiki/Dynamo_theory\">dynamo</a> ceased to function and the planet's magnetic field faded away.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-plates-45\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 44;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[44]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>During the <a href=\"/wiki/Formation_and_evolution_of_the_Solar_System\">Solar System's formation</a>, Mars was created as the result of a <a href=\"/wiki/Stochastic_process\">stochastic process</a> of run-away accretion out of the <a href=\"/wiki/Protoplanetary_disk\">protoplanetary disk</a> that orbited the Sun. Mars has many distinctive chemical features caused by its position in the Solar System. Elements with comparatively low boiling points, such as <a href=\"/wiki/Chlorine\">chlorine</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Phosphorus\">phosphorus</a>, and <a href=\"/wiki/Sulphur\">sulphur</a>, are much more common on Mars than Earth; these elements were probably removed from areas closer to the Sun by the young star's energetic <a href=\"/wiki/Solar_wind\">solar wind</a>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-ssr96_1_4_197-46\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 45;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[45]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>After the formation of the planets, all were subjected to the so-called \"<a href=\"/wiki/Late_Heavy_Bombardment\">Late Heavy Bombardment</a>\". About 60% of the surface of Mars shows a record of impacts from that era,<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-zharkov93-47\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 46;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[46]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-icarus165_1-48\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 47;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[47]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-barlow88-49\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 48;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[48]</span></a></span> whereas much of the remaining surface is probably underlain by immense impact basins caused by those events. There is evidence of an enormous impact basin in the northern hemisphere of Mars, spanning <span>10,600 by 8,500</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span>km (6,600 by 5,300</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span>mi)</span>, or roughly
05-23 18:38:57.848 debug OkHttp four times larger than the Moon's <a href=\"/wiki/South_Pole__Aitken_basin\">South Pole Aitken basin</a>, the largest impact basin yet discovered.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-northcratersn-17\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 16;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[16]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-northcraterguard-18\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 17;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[17]</span></a></span> This theory suggests that Mars was struck by a <a href=\"/wiki/Pluto\">Pluto</a>-sized body about four billion years ago. The event, thought to be the cause of the <a href=\"/wiki/Martian_hemispheric_dichotomy\">Martian hemispheric dichotomy</a>, created the smooth <a href=\"/wiki/Borealis_basin\">Borealis basin</a> that covers 40% of the planet.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-sciam080627-50\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 49;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[49]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-nyt080626-51\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 50;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[50]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<figure class=\"mw-default-size\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Eso1509a_-_Mars_planet.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c3/Eso1509a_-_Mars_planet.jpg/220px-Eso1509a_-_Mars_planet.jpg\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c3/Eso1509a_-_Mars_planet.jpg/440px-Eso1509a_-_Mars_planet.jpg 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c3/Eso1509a_-_Mars_planet.jpg/330px-Eso1509a_-_Mars_planet.jpg 1.5x\" height=\"135\" width=\"220\"></a><figcaption>Artist's impression of how Mars may have looked four billion years ago<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-52\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 51;\" class=\"image\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[51]</span></a></span></figcaption></figure>\n\n<p>The geological history of Mars can be split into many periods, but the following are the three primary periods:<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-jog91-53\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 52;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[52]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-ssr_96_1_4-54\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 53;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[53]</span></a></span></p>\n<ul><li id=\"mwng\"> <b><a href=\"/wiki/Noachian\">Noachian</a> period</b> (named after <a href=\"/wiki/Noachis_Terra\">Noachis Terra</a>): Formation of the oldest extant surfaces of Mars, 4.5 billion years ago to 3.5 billion years ago. Noachian age surfaces are scarred by many large impact craters. The <a href=\"/wiki/Tharsis\">Tharsis</a> bulge, a volcanic upland, is thought to have formed during this period, with extensive flooding by liquid water late in the period.</li>\n<li id=\"mwow\"> <b><a href=\"/wiki/Hesperian\">Hesperian</a> period</b> (named after <a href=\"/wiki/Hesperia_Planum\">Hesperia Planum</a>): 3.5 billion years ago to 2.93.3 billion years ago. The Hesperian period is marked by the formation of extensive lava plains.</li>\n<li id=\"mwpw\"> <b><a href=\"/wiki/Amazonian_(Mars)\">Amazonian period</a></b> (named after <a href=\"/wiki/Amazonis_Planitia\">Amazonis Planitia</a>): 2.93.3 billion years ago to present. Amazonian regions have few <a href=\"/wiki/Impact_event\">meteorite impact</a> craters, but are otherwise quite varied. <a href=\"/wiki/Olympus_Mons\">Olympus Mons</a> formed during this period, along with lava flows elsewhere on Mars.</li></ul>\n\n<p>Some geological activity is still taking place on Mars. The <a href=\"/wiki/Athabasca_Valles\">Athabasca Valles</a> is home to sheet-like lava flows up to about 200 <a href=\"/wiki/Mya_(unit)\">Mya</a>. Water flows in the <a href=\"/wiki/Graben\">grabens</a> called the <a href=\"/wiki/Cerberus_Fossae\">Cerberus Fossae</a> occurred less than 20 Mya, indicating equally recent volcanic intrusions.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-ag44_4-55\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 54;\"><span class=\"mw-

It is a <a href=\"/wiki/Giant_planet\">giant planet</a> with a <a href=\"/wiki/Mass\">mass</a> one-thousandth that of the Sun, but two and a half times that of all the other planets in the Solar System combined. Jupiter is a <a href=\"/wiki/Gas_giant\">gas giant</a>, along with <a href=\"/wiki/Saturn\">Saturn</a>. (<a href=\"/wiki/Uranus\">Uranus</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Neptune\">Neptune</a> are <a href=\"/wiki/Ice_giant\">ice giants</a>.) Jupiter was known to <a href=\"/wiki/Astronomer\">astronomers</a> of ancient times.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-13\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 11;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[11]</span></a></span> The <a href=\"/wiki/Ancient_Rome\">Romans</a> named it after <a href=\"/wiki/Roman_mythology\">their god</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Jupiter_(mythology)\">Jupiter</a>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-14\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 12;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[12]</span></a></span> When viewed from <a href=\"/wiki/Earth\">Earth</a>, Jupiter can reach an <a href=\"/wiki/Apparent_magnitude\">apparent magnitude</a> of 2.94, bright enough for its reflected light to cast shadows,<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-15\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 13;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[13]</span></a></span> and making it on average the third-brightest object in the <a href=\"/wiki/Night_sky\">night sky</a> after the <a href=\"/wiki/Moon\">Moon</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Venus\">Venus</a>.</p></span><div class=\"hatnote\">This article is about the planet. For the Roman god, see <a href=\"/wiki/Jupiter_(mythology)\">Jupiter (mythology)</a>. It may also have a rocky core of heavier elements,<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-coreuncertainty-16\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 14;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[14]</span></a></span> but like the other giant planets, Jupiter lacks a well-defined solid surface. Because of its rapid rotation, the planet's shape is that of an <a href=\"/wiki/Oblate_spheroid\">oblate spheroid</a> (it has a slight but noticeable bulge around the equator). The outer atmosphere is visibly segregated into several bands at different latitudes, resulting in turbulence and storms along their interacting boundaries. A prominent result is the <a href=\"/wiki/Great_Red_Spot\">Great Red Spot</a>, a giant storm that is known to have existed since at least the 17th century when it was first seen by <a href=\"/wiki/Telescope\">telescope</a>. Surrounding Jupiter is a faint <a href=\"/wiki/Planetary_ring\">planetary ring</a> system and a powerful <a href=\"/wiki/Magnetosphere\">magnetosphere</a>. Jupiter has at least <a href=\"/wiki/Moons_of_Jupiter\">67 moons</a>, including the four large <a href=\"/wiki/Galilean_moons\">Galilean moons</a> discovered by <a href=\"/wiki/Galileo_Galilei\">Galileo Galilei</a> in 1610. <a href=\"/wiki/Ganymede_(moon)\">Ganymede</a>, the largest of these, has a diameter greater than that of the planet <a href=\"/wiki/Mercury_(planet)\">Mercury</a>.</p>\n\n<p>Jupiter has been explored on several occasions by <a href=\"/wiki/Robotic_spacecraft\">robotic spacecraft</a>, most notably during the early <i><a href=\"/wiki/Pioneer_program\">Pioneer</a></i> and <i><a href=\"/wiki/Voyager_program\">Voyager</a></i> <a href=\"/wiki/Planetary_flyby\">flyby</a> missions and later by the <a href=\"/wiki/Galileo_(spacecraft)\"><i>Galileo</i> orbiter</a>. Jupiter was most recently visited by a probe in late February 2007, when <i><a href=\"/wiki/New_Horizons\">New Horizons</a></i> <a href=\"/wiki/Gravitational_slingshot\">used Jupiter's gravity</a> to increase its speed and bend its trajectory en route to <a href=\"/wiki/Pluto\">Pluto</a>. The next probe to visit the planet will be <i><a href=\"/wiki/Juno_(spacecraft)\">Juno</a></i>, which is expected to arrive in July 2016. Future targets for exploration in the Jupiter system include the probable ice-covered liquid ocean of its moon <a href=\"/wiki/Europa_(moon)\">Europa</a>.</p>\n\n"},{"id":1,"toclevel":1,"anchor":"Formation_and_migration","line":"Formation and migration"},{"id":2,"toclevel":1,"anchor":"Structure","line":"Structure"},{"id":3,"toclevel":2,"anchor":"Composition","line":"Composition"},{"id":4,"toclevel":2,"anchor":"Mass_and_size","line":"Mass and size"},{"id":5,"toclevel":2,"anchor":"Internal_structure","line":"Internal structure"},{"id":6,"toclevel":1,"anchor":"Atmosphere","line":"Atmosphere"},{"id":7,"toclevel":2,"anchor":"Cloud_layers","line":"Cloud layers"},{"id":8,"toclevel":2,"anchor":"Great_Red_Spot_and_other_vortice

As Jupiter came toward the inner Solar System, in what theorists call the <a href=\"/wiki/Grand_Tack_Hypothesis\">Grand Tack Hypothesis</a>, gravitational tugs and pulls occurred causing a series of collisions between the super-Earths as their orbits began to overlap.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-17\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 15;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[15]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>Astronomers have discovered nearly 500 planetary systems each with multiple planets, and typically these systems include a few planets with masses several times greater than Earth's (super-Earths), orbiting closer to their star than Mercury is to the Sun, and Jupiter-like gas giants are also often found close to their star.</p>\n\n<p>Jupiter moving out of the inner Solar System would have allowed the formation of inner planets, including <a href=\"/wiki/Earth\">Earth</a>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-18\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 16;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[16]</span></a></span></p>\n\n","toclevel":1,"line":"Formation and migration","anchor":"Formation_and_migration"},{"id":2,"text":"\n<p>Jupiter is composed primarily of gaseous and liquid matter. It is the largest of the four giant planets in the Solar System and hence its largest planet. A helium atom has about four times as much mass as a hydrogen atom, so the composition changes when described as the proportion of mass contributed by different atoms. Thus, <a href=\"/wiki/Atmosphere_of_Jupiter\">Jupiter's atmosphere</a> is approximately 75% hydrogen and 24% helium by mass, with the remaining one percent of the mass consisting of other elements. The interior contains denser materials, such that the distribution is roughly 71% hydrogen, 24% helium, and 5% other elements by mass. The atmosphere contains trace amounts of <a href=\"/wiki/Methane\">methane</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Water_vapor\">water vapor</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Ammonia\">ammonia</a>, and <a href=\"/wiki/Silicon\">silicon</a>-based compounds. This core is surrounded by a deep layer of <a href=\"/wiki/Metallic_hydrogen\">metallic hydrogen</a>, an intermediate layer of <a href=\"/wiki/Liquid_hydrogen\">liquid hydrogen</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Liquid_helium\">liquid helium</a>, and finally outside the <a href=\"/wiki/Frenkel_line\">Frenkel line</a> a gaseous outer layer.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Composition_ref-16\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 15;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[15]</span></a></span> Saturn has a pale yellow hue due to <a href=\"/wiki/Ammonia\">ammonia</a> crystals in its upper atmosphere. <a href=\"/wiki/Electrical_current\">Electrical current</a> within the metallic hydrogen layer is thought to give rise to Saturn's planetary <a href=\"/wiki/Magnetic_field\">magnetic field</a>, which is weaker than Earth's, but has a <a href=\"/wiki/Magnetic_moment\">magnetic moment</a> 580 times that of Earth due to Saturn's larger size. Saturn's magnetic field strength is around one-twentieth of Jupiter's.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-mag-17\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 16;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[16]</span></a></span> The outer <a href=\"/wiki/Atmosphere\">atmosphere</a> is generally bland and lacking in contrast, although long-lived features can appear. <a href=\"/wiki/Wind_speed\">Wind speeds</a> on Saturn can reach <span>1,800</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span>km/h (500</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span>m/s)</span>, higher than on Jupiter, but not as high as those on <a href=\"/wiki/Neptune\">Neptune</a>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Science_Ch._2004-18\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 17;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[17]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>Saturn has a prominent <a href=\"/wiki/Rings_of_Saturn\">ring system</a> that consists of nine continuous main rings and three discontinuous arcs and that is composed mostly of ice particles with a smaller amount of rocky debris and <a href=\"/wiki/Cosmic_dust\">dust</a>. Sixty-two<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-19\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 18;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[18]</span></a></span> <a href=\"/wiki/Moons_of_Saturn\">moons</a> are known to orbit Saturn, of which fifty-three are officially named. This does not include the hundreds of <a href=\"/wiki/Moonlet\">moonlets</a> comprising the rings. <a href=\"/wiki/Titan_(moon)\">Titan</a>, Saturn's largest moon, and the second-largest in the Solar System, is larger than the planet <a href=\"/wiki/Mercury_(planet)\">Mercury</a>, although less massive, and is the only moon in the Solar System to have a substantial atmosphere.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Titan_ref-20\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 19;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[19]</span></a></span></p>\n<div class=\"toclimit-3\"><meta property=\"mw:PageProp/toc\"></div>\n\n"},{"id":1

05-23 18:39:12.728 debug OkHttp {"sections":[{"id":1,"text":"\n<figure class=\"mw-default-size mw-halign-left\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Saturn,_Earth_size_comparison.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/39/Saturn%2C_Earth_size_comparison.jpg/220px-Saturn%2C_Earth_size_comparison.jpg\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/39/Saturn%2C_Earth_size_comparison.jpg/440px-Saturn%2C_Earth_size_comparison.jpg 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/39/Saturn%2C_Earth_size_comparison.jpg/330px-Saturn%2C_Earth_size_comparison.jpg 1.5x\" height=\"191\" width=\"220\"></a><figcaption>Composite image roughly comparing the sizes of Saturn and Earth</figcaption></figure>\n\n<p>Saturn is a <a href=\"/wiki/Gas_giant\">gas giant</a> because it is predominantly composed of hydrogen and helium ('gas'). It lacks a definite surface, though it may have a solid core.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-melosh2011-21\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 20;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[20]</span></a></span> Saturn's rotation causes it to have the shape of an <a href=\"/wiki/Oblate_spheroid\">oblate spheroid</a>; that is, it is flattened at the poles and bulges at its equator. Its equatorial and polar radii differ by almost 10%: 60,268<span>&nbsp;</span>km versus 54,364<span>&nbsp;</span>km, respectively.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-fact-4\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 4;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[4]</span></a></span> Jupiter, <a href=\"/wiki/Uranus\">Uranus</a>, and <a href=\"/wiki/Neptune\">Neptune</a>, the other giant planets in the Solar System, are also oblate but to a lesser extent. Saturn is the only planet of the Solar System that is less dense than waterabout 30% less.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-preserve-22\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 21;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[21]</span></a></span> Although Saturn's <a href=\"/wiki/Planetary_core\">core</a> is considerably denser than water, the average <a href=\"/wiki/Relative_density\">specific density</a> of the planet is 0.69<span>&nbsp;</span>g/cm<sup id=\"mwOg\">3</sup> due to the atmosphere. Jupiter has 318<span>&nbsp;</span>times the Earth's mass,<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Jupiter_fact-23\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 22;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[22]</span></a></span> while Saturn is 95 times the mass of the <a href=\"/wiki/Earth\">Earth</a>,<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-fact-4\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 4;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[4]</span></a></span> Together, Jupiter and Saturn hold 92% of the total planetary mass in the Solar System.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-ssr152_1_423-24\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 23;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[23]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>On 8 January 2015, NASA reported determining the center of the planet Saturn and its <a href=\"/wiki/Moons_of_Saturn\">family of moons</a> to within <span>4</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span>km (2.5</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span>mi)</span>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-NASA-20150108-25\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 24;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[24]</span></a></span></p>\n\n","toclevel":1,"line":"Physical characteristics","anchor":"Physical_characteristics"},{"id":2,"text":"\n<p>Despite consisting mostly of hydrogen and helium, most of Saturn's mass is not in the <a href=\"/wiki/Gas\">gas</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Phase_(matter)\">phase</a>, because hydrogen becomes a <a href=\"/wiki/Ideal_solution\">non-ideal liquid</a> when the density is above 0.01<span>&nbsp;</span>g/cm<sup id=\"mwRg\">3</sup>, which is reached at a radius containing 99.9% of Saturn's mass. The temperature, pressure, and density inside Saturn all rise steadily toward the core, which causes hydrogen to transition into a metal in the deeper layers.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-ssr152_1_423-24\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 23;\"><span class=\"mw-
05-23 18:39:12.809 debug OkHttp reflink-text\">[23]</span></a></span></p>\n \n<p>Standard planetary models suggest that the interior of Saturn is similar to that of <a href=\"/wiki/Jupiter\">Jupiter</a>, having a small rocky core surrounded by <a href=\"/wiki/Hydrogen\">hydrogen</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Helium\">helium</a> with trace amounts of various <a href=\"/wiki/Volatiles\">volatiles</a>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-guillot_et_al2009-26\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 25;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[25]</span></a></span> This core is similar in composition to the Earth, but more dense. Examination of Saturn's <a href=\"/wiki/Gravitational_moment\">gravitational moment</a>, in combination with physical models of the interior, allowed French astronomers Didier Saumon and Tristan Guillot to place constraints on the mass of Saturn's core. In 2004, they estimated that the core must be 922<span>&nbsp;</span>times the mass of the Earth,<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-science305_5689_1414-27\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 26;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[26]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-apj609_2_1170-28\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 27;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[27]</span></a></span> which corresponds to a diameter of about 25,000<span>&nbsp;</span>km.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-29\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 28;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[28]</span></a></span> This is surrounded by a thicker liquid <a href=\"/wiki/Metallic_hydrogen\">metallic hydrogen</a> layer, followed by a liquid layer of helium-saturated <a href=\"/wiki/Molecular_hydrogen\">molecular hydrogen</a> that gradually transitions to a gas with increasing altitude. The outermost layer spans 1,000<span>&nbsp;</span>km and consists of gas.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-faure_mensing2007-30\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 29;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[29]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-NMM_Saturn-31\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 30;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[30]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-32\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 31;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[31]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>Saturn has a hot interior, reaching 11,700<span>&nbsp;</span>C at its core, and it radiates 2.5 times more energy into space than it receives from the Sun. Jupiter's <a href=\"/wiki/Thermal_energy\">thermal energy</a> is generated by the <a href=\"/wiki/KelvinHelmholtz_mechanism\">KelvinHelmholtz mechanism</a> of slow <a href=\"/wiki/Gravitational_compression\">gravitational compression</a>, but this alone may not be sufficient to explain heat production for Saturn, because it is less massive. An alternative or additional mechanism may be generation of heat through the \"raining out\" of droplets of helium deep in Saturn's interior. As the droplets descend through the lower-density hydrogen, the process releases heat by <a href=\"/wiki/Friction\">friction</a> and leaves Saturn's outer layers depleted of helium.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-de_pater_lissauer2010-33\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 32;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[32]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-nasa_saturn-34\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 33;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[33]</span></a></span> These descending droplets may have accumulated into a helium shell surrounding the core.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-guillot_et_al2009-26\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 25;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[25]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<div class=\"center\">\n<div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"background:none;border:none;max-width:800px;\">\n<div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div style=\"float: left; margin-top: 0.25em; width: 11px; height: 9.5px;\"><div style=\"position: relative; float: left; width: 0px; height: 0px; -webkit-transform: rotate(360deg); border-style: solid inset;

by volume.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-35\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 34;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[34]</span></a></span> The proportion of helium is significantly deficient compared to the abundance of this element in the Sun.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-guillot_et_al2009-26\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 25;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[25]</span></a></span> The quantity of elements heavier than helium is not known precisely, but the proportions are assumed to match the primordial abundances from the formation of the Solar System. The total mass of these heavier elements is estimated to be 1931<span>&nbsp;</span>times the mass of the Earth, with a significant fraction located in Saturn's core region.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-science286-36\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 35;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[35]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>Trace amounts of ammonia, <a href=\"/wiki/Acetylene\">acetylene</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Ethane\">ethane</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Propane\">propane</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Phosphine\">phosphine</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Methane\">methane</a> have been detected in Saturn's atmosphere.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-baas15_831-37\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 36;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[36]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-cain2009_24029-38\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 37;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[37]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-pfsaa2008-39\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 38;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[38]</span></a></span> The upper clouds are composed of ammonia crystals, while the lower level clouds appear to consist of either <a href=\"/wiki/Ammonium_hydrosulfide\">ammonium hydrosulfide</a> (NH<sub id=\"mwaA\">4</sub>SH) or water.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-martinez20050905-40\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 39;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[39]</span></a></span> <a href=\"/wiki/Ultraviolet\">Ultraviolet</a> radiation from the Sun causes methane <a href=\"/wiki/Photolysis\">photolysis</a> in the upper atmosphere, leading to a series of <a href=\"/wiki/Hydrocarbon\">hydrocarbon</a> chemical reactions with the resulting products being carried downward by eddies and diffusion. It has the third-largest planetary radius and fourth-largest planetary mass in the <a href=\"/wiki/Solar_System\">Solar System</a>. Uranus is similar in composition to <a href=\"/wiki/Neptune\">Neptune</a>, and both have different bulk chemical composition from that of the larger <a href=\"/wiki/Gas_giant\">gas giants</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Jupiter\">Jupiter</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Saturn\">Saturn</a>. For this reason, scientists often classify Uranus and Neptune as \"<a href=\"/wiki/Ice_giant\">ice giants</a>\" to distinguish them from the gas giants. Uranus's atmosphere is similar to Jupiter's and Saturn's in its primary composition of <a href=\"/wiki/Hydrogen\">hydrogen</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Helium\">helium</a>, but it contains more \"<a href=\"/wiki/Volatiles\">ices</a>\" such as water, <a href=\"/wiki/Ammonia\">ammonia</a>, and <a href=\"/wiki/Methane\">methane</a>, along with traces of other <a href=\"/wiki/Hydrocarbon\">hydrocarbons</a>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Lunine_1993-14\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 11;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[11]</span></a></span> It is the coldest planetary <a href=\"/wiki/Atmosphere\">atmosphere</a> in the Solar System, with a minimum temperature of <span>49</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span>K (224.2</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span>C)</span>, and has a complex, layered <a href=\"/wiki/Cloud\">cloud</a> structure with water thought to make up the lowest clouds and methane the uppermost layer of clouds.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Lunine_1993-14\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 11;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[11]</span></a></span> The interior of Uranus is mainly composed of ices and rock.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Podolak_Weizman_et_al._1995-13\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 10;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[10]</span></a></span></p></span><div class=\"hatnote\">This article is about the planet. Like the other <a href=\"/wiki/Giant_planet\">giant planets</a>, Uranus has a <a href=\"/wiki/Rings_of_Uranus\">ring system</a>, a <a href=\"/wiki/Magnetosphere\">magnetosphere</a>, and numerous <a href=\"/wiki/Natural_satellite\">moons</a>. The Uranian system has a unique configuration among those of the planets because its <a href=\"/wiki/Axis_of_rotation\">axis of rotation</a> is tilted sideways, nearly into the plane of its solar orbit. Its north and south poles, therefore, lie where most other planets have their <a href=\"/wiki/Equator\">equators</a>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Smith_Soderblom_et_al._1986-18\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 15;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[15]</span></a></span> In 1986, images from <a href=\"/wiki/Voyager_2\">Voyager&nbsp;2</a> showed Uranus as an almost featureless planet in visible light, without the cloud bands or storms associated with the other giant planets.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Smith_Soderblom_et_al._1986-18\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 15;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[15]</span></a></span> Observations from Earth have shown seasonal change and increased weather activity as Uranus approached its <a href=\"/wiki/Equinox\">equinox</a> in 2007. Wind speeds can reach 250 metres per second (900<span>&nbsp;</span>km/h, 560<span>&nbsp;</span>mph).<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Sromovsky_.26_Fry_2005-19\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 16;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[16]</span></a></span></p>\n\n"},{"id":1,"toclevel":1,"anchor":"History","line":"History"},{"id":2,"toclevel":2,"anchor":"Discovery","line":"Discovery"},{"id":3,"toclevel":2,"anchor":"Name","line":"Name"},{"id":4,"toclevel":1,"anchor":"Orbit_and_rotation","line":"Orbit and rotation"},{"id":5,"toclevel":2,"anchor":"Axial_tilt","line":"Axial tilt"},{"id":6,"toclevel":2,"anchor":"Visibility","line":"Visibility"},{"id":7,"toclevel":1,"anchor":"Internal_structure","line":"Internal structure"},{"id":8,"toclevel":2,"anchor":"Internal_heat","line":"Internal heat"},{"id":9,"toclevel":1,"anchor":"Atmosphere","line":"Atmosphere"},{"id":10,"toclevel":2,"anchor":"Composition","line":"Composition"},{"id":11,"toclevel":2,"anchor":"Troposphere","line":"Troposphere"},{"id":12,"toclevel":2,"anchor":"Upper_atmosphere","line":"Upper atmosphere"},{"id":13,"toclevel":1,"anchor":"Planetary_rings","line":"Planetary rings"},{"id":14,"toclevel":1,"anchor":"Magnetosphere","line":"Magnetosphere"},{"id":15,"toclevel":1,"anchor":"Climate","line":"Climate"},{"id":16,"toclevel":2,"anchor":"Banded_structure.2C_winds_and_clouds","line":"Banded structure, winds and clouds"},{"id":17,"toclevel":2,"anchor":"Seasonal_variation","line":"Seasonal variation"},{"id":18,"toclevel":1,"anchor":"Formation","line":"Formation"},{"id":19,"toclevel":1,"an
