05-23 18:39:20.598 debug OkHttp {"sections":[{"id":1,"text":"\n<p>Like the five <a href=\"/wiki/Classical_planet\">classical planets</a>, Uranus is visible to the naked eye, but was never recognized as a planet by ancient observers because of its dimness and slow orbit.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-20\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 17;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[17]</span></a></span> Sir <a href=\"/wiki/William_Herschel\">William Herschel</a> announced its discovery on 13 March 1781, expanding the known boundaries of the <a href=\"/wiki/Solar_System\">Solar System</a> for the first time in history and making Uranus the first planet discovered with a <a href=\"/wiki/Telescope\">telescope</a>.</p>\n\n","toclevel":1,"line":"History","anchor":"History"},{"id":2,"text":"\n<figure class=\"mw-default-size mw-halign-left\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:William_Herschel01.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/36/William_Herschel01.jpg/170px-William_Herschel01.jpg\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/36/William_Herschel01.jpg/340px-William_Herschel01.jpg 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/36/William_Herschel01.jpg/255px-William_Herschel01.jpg 1.5x\" height=\"208\" width=\"170\"></a><figcaption><a href=\"/wiki/William_Herschel\" class=\"image\">William Herschel</a>, discoverer of Uranus</figcaption></figure>\n\n<p>Uranus had been observed on many occasions before its recognition as a planet, but it was generally mistaken for a star. Possibly the earliest known observation was by <a href=\"/wiki/Hipparchos\">Hipparchos</a>, who in 128 BC may have recorded it as a star for his <a href=\"/wiki/Star_catalogue\">star catalogue</a> that was later incorporated into <a href=\"/wiki/Ptolemy\">Ptolemy</a>'s <a href=\"/wiki/Almagest\">Almagest</a>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-21\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 18;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[18]</span></a></span> The earliest definite sighting was in 1690 when <a href=\"/wiki/John_Flamsteed\">John Flamsteed</a> observed it at least six times, cataloguing it as 34 <a href=\"/wiki/Taurus_(constellation)\">Tauri</a>. The French astronomer <a href=\"/wiki/Pierre_Lemonnier\">Pierre Lemonnier</a> observed Uranus at least twelve times between 1750 and 1769,<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-22\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 19;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[19]</span></a></span> including on four consecutive nights.</p>\n\n<p>Sir <a href=\"/wiki/William_Herschel\">William Herschel</a> observed Uranus on 13 March 1781 from the garden of his house at 19 New King Street in <a href=\"/wiki/Bath,_Somerset\">Bath, Somerset</a>, England (now the <a href=\"/wiki/Herschel_Museum_of_Astronomy\">Herschel Museum of Astronomy</a>),<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-23\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 20;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[20]</span></a></span> and initially reported it (on 26 April 1781) as a <a href=\"/wiki/Comet\">comet</a>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-24\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 21;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[21]</span></a></span> Herschel \"engaged in a series of observations on the parallax of the fixed stars\",<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Ref-1-25\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 22;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[22]</span></a></span> using a telescope of his own design.</p>\n\n<p>He recorded in his journal \"In the quartile near <a href=\"/wiki/Zeta_Tauri\"> Tauri</a><span>&nbsp;</span>... either [a] Nebulous star or perhaps a comet\".<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-26\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 23;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[23]</span></a></span> On 17 March he noted, \"I looked for the Comet or Nebulous Star and found that it is a Comet, for it has changed its place\".<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-27\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 24;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[24]</span></a></span> Whe
05-23 18:39:20.630 debug OkHttp n he presented his discovery to the <a href=\"/wiki/Royal_Society\">Royal Society</a>, he continued to assert that he had found a comet, but also implicitly compared it to a planet:<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Ref-1-25\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 22;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[22]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<blockquote class=\"templatequote\"><i>\"The power I had on when I first saw the comet was 227. From experience I know that the diameters of the fixed stars are not proportionally magnified with higher powers, as planets are; therefore I now put the powers at 460 and 932, and found that the diameter of the comet increased in proportion to the power, as it ought to be, on the supposition of its not being a fixed star, while the diameters of the stars to which I compared it were not increased in the same ratio. Moreover, the comet being magnified much beyond what its light would admit of, appeared hazy and ill-defined with these great powers, while the stars preserved that lustre and distinctness which from many thousand observations I knew they would retain. The sequel has shown that my surmises were well-founded, this proving to be the Comet we have lately observed\"</i>.\n</blockquote>\n\n<figure class=\"mw-default-size mw-halign-left\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:HerschelTelescope.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d7/HerschelTelescope.jpg/190px-HerschelTelescope.jpg\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d7/HerschelTelescope.jpg/380px-HerschelTelescope.jpg 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d7/HerschelTelescope.jpg/285px-HerschelTelescope.jpg 1.5x\" height=\"244\" width=\"190\"></a><figcaption>Replica of the telescope used by Herschel to discover Uranus</figcaption></figure>\n\n<p>Herschel notified the <a href=\"/wiki/Astronomer_Royal\">Astronomer Royal</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Nevil_Maskelyne\">Nevil Maskelyne</a>, of his discovery and received this flummoxed reply from him on 23 April: \"I don't know what to call it. It is as likely to be a regular planet moving in an orbit nearly circular to the sun as a Comet moving in a very eccentric ellipsis. I have not yet seen any coma or tail to it\".<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-28\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 25;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[25]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>Although Herschel continued to describe his new object as a comet, other astronomers had already begun to suspect otherwise. Finnish-Swedish astronomer <a href=\"/wiki/Anders_Johan_Lexell\">Anders Johan Lexell</a>, working in Russia, was the first to compute the orbit of the new object<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-lexell-29\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 26;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[26]</span></a></span> and its nearly circular orbit led him to a conclusion that it was a planet rather than a comet. Berlin astronomer <a href=\"/wiki/Johann_Elert_Bode\">Johann Elert Bode</a> described Herschel's discovery as \"a moving star that can be deemed a hitherto unknown planet-like object circulating beyond the orbit of Saturn\".<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-30\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 27;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[27]</span></a></span> Bode concluded that its near-circular orbit was more like a planet than a comet.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-31\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 28;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[28]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>The object was soon universally accepted as a new planet. By 1783, Herschel acknowledged this to Royal Society president <a href=\"/wiki/Joseph_Banks\">Joseph Banks</a>: \"By the observation of the most eminent Astronomers in Europe it appears that the new star, which I had the honour of pointing out to them in March 1781, is a Primary Planet of our Solar System.\"<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Dreyer-32\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 29;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\"
05-23 18:39:20.630 debug OkHttp >[29]</span></a></span> In recognition of his achievement, <a href=\"/wiki/George_III_of_the_United_Kingdom\">King George III</a> gave Herschel an annual <a href=\"/wiki/Stipend\">stipend</a> of 200 on condition that he move to Windsor so that the Royal Family could look through his telescopes.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Miner12-33\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 30;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[30]</span></a></span></p>\n\n","toclevel":2,"line":"Discovery","anchor":"Discovery"},{"id":3,"text":"\n<p>Uranus is named after the ancient Greek deity of the sky <a href=\"/wiki/Uranus_(mythology)\">Uranus</a> (<a href=\"/wiki/Ancient_Greek\">Ancient&nbsp;Greek</a><span>: </span><span><a href=\"//en.wiktionary.org/wiki/#Ancient Greek\"></a></span>), the father of <a href=\"/wiki/Cronus\">Cronus</a> (<a href=\"/wiki/Saturn_(mythology)\">Saturn</a>) and grandfather of <a href=\"/wiki/Zeus\">Zeus</a> (<a href=\"/wiki/Jupiter_(mythology)\">Jupiter</a>), which in Latin became \"ranus\".<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-OED-1\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 1;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[1]</span></a></span> It is the only planet whose name is derived from a figure of <a href=\"/wiki/Greek_mythology\">Greek mythology</a>. The adjective of Uranus is \"Uranian\".<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-34\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 31;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[31]</span></a></span> The pronunciation of the name <i>Uranus</i> preferred among <a href=\"/wiki/Astronomers\">astronomers</a> is <span><span class=\"ipa_button\"></span><span class=\"nowrap\" style=\"display: none;\"><span class=\"IPA nopopups\"><a href=\"/wiki/Help:IPA_for_English\">/<span style=\"border-bottom:1px dotted\"><span></span><span>jr</span><span></span><span>n</span><span></span><span>s</span></span>/</a></span></span></span>,<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-BBCOUP-2\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 2;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[2]</span></a></span> with stress on the first syllable as in Latin <i>ranus,</i> in contrast to <span><span class=\"ipa_button\"></span><span class=\"nowrap\" style=\"display: none;\"><span class=\"IPA nopopups\"><a href=\"/wiki/Help:IPA_for_English\">/<span style=\"border-bottom:1px dotted\"><span>j</span><span></span><span></span><span>r</span><span>e</span><span>n</span><span></span><span>s</span></span>/</a></span></span></span>, with stress on the second syllable and a <a href=\"/wiki/Vowel_length#Traditional_long_and_short_vowels_in_English_orthography\">long <i>a</i></a>, though both are considered acceptable.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-35\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 4;\" data-mw-group=\"lower-alpha\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[lower-alpha 4]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>Consensus on the name was not reached until almost 70 years after the planet's discovery. During the original discussions following discovery, Maskelyne asked Herschel to \"do the astronomical world the faver <span> </span>[<i><a href=\"/wiki/Sic\">sic</a></i>] to give a name to your planet, which is entirely your own, [and] which we are so much obliged to you for the discovery of\".<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-37\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 33;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[33]</span></a></span> In response to Maskelyne's request, Herschel decided to name the object <i>Georgium Sidus</i> (George's Star), or the \"Georgian Planet\" in honour of his new patron, King George III.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-38\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 34;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[34]</span></a></span> He explained this decision in a letter to Joseph Banks:<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Dreyer-32\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 29;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[29]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<blockquote class=\"templatequote\">In the fabulous ages of ancient times the appellations of Mercury, Venus,
05-23 18:39:20.681 debug OkHttp Mars, Jupiter and Saturn were given to the Planets, as being the names of their principal heroes and divinities. In the present more philosophical era it would hardly be allowable to have recourse to the same method and call it Juno, Pallas, Apollo or Minerva, for a name to our new heavenly body. The first consideration of any particular event, or remarkable incident, seems to be its chronology: if in any future age it should be asked, when this last-found Planet was discovered? It would be a very satisfactory answer to say, 'In the reign of King George the Third'.\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>Herschel's proposed name was not popular outside Britain, and alternatives were soon proposed. Astronomer <a href=\"/wiki/Jrme_Lalande\">Jrme Lalande</a> proposed that it be named <i>Herschel</i> in honour of its discoverer.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Francisca-39\" which was supported by other astronomers who liked the idea to commemorate the victories of the British <a href=\"/wiki/Royal_Navy\">Royal Naval</a> fleet in the course of the <a href=\"/wiki/American_Revolutionary_War\">American Revolutionary War</a> by calling the new planet even <i>Neptune George III</i> or <i>Neptune Great Britain</i>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"/wiki/Uranus_(mythology)\">Ouranos</a>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Bode-40\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 36;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[36]</span></a></span> Bode argued that the name should follow the mythology so as not to stand out as different from the other planets, and that Uranus was an appropriate name as the father of the first generation of the <a href=\"/wiki/Titan_(mythology)\">Titans</a>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Bode-40\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 36;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[36]</span></a></span> He also noted that elegance of the name in that just as <a href=\"/wiki/Saturn_(mythology)\">Saturn</a> was the father of <a href=\"/wiki/Jupiter_(mythology)\">Jupiter</a>, the new planet should be named after the father of Saturn.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Miner12-33\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 30;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[30]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Bode-40\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 36;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[36]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-planetsbeyond-41\" In a letter to Herschel, Lalande described it as \"un globe surmont par la premire lettre de votre nom\" (\"a globe surmounted by the first letter of your surname\").<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Francisca-39\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 35;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[35]</span></a></span> A later proposal, ,<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-symbol_later-45\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 6;\" data-mw-group=\"lower-alpha\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[lower-alpha 6]</span></a></span> is a hybrid of the symbols for <a href=\"/wiki/Mars\">Mars</a> and the <a href=\"/wiki/Sun\">Sun</a> because Uranus was the Sky in Greek mythology, which was thought to be dominated by the combined powers of the Sun and Mars.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-46\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 40;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[40]</span></a></span></p> \n\n<p>Uranus is called by a variety of translations in other languages. In <a href=\"/wiki/Chinese_language\">Chinese</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Japanese_language\">Japanese</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Korean_language\">Korean</a>, and <a href=\"/wiki/Vietnamese_language\">Vietnamese</a>, its name is literally translated as the \"sky king star\" (<span></span>).<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-47\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 41;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[41]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-48\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 42;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[42]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-49\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 43;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[43]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-50\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 44;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[44]</span></a></span> In <a href=\"/wiki/Thai_language\">Thai</a>, its official name is <i>Dao Yurenat</i> (), as in English. Its other name in Thai is <i>Dao Maritayu</i> (, Star of Mtyu), after the <a href=\"/wiki/Sanskrit_language\">Sanskrit</a> word for \"death\", <a href=\"/wiki/Mrtyu\">Mrtyu</a> (). In <a href=\"/wiki/Hawaiian_language\">Hawaiian</a>, its name is <i>Heleekala</i>. In <a href=\"/wiki/Mori_language\">Mori</a>, its name is <i>Whrangi</i>. <span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-51\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 45;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[45]</span></a></span> <span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-52\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 46;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[46]</span></a></span> It is also named in Mori as <i>Rangip</i>. Its average distance from the Sun is roughly 3 <a href=\"/wiki/1,000,000,000_(number)\">billion</a><span>&nbsp;</span>km (about 20 <a href=\"/wiki/Astronomical_Units\">AU</a>). The difference between its minimum and maximum distance from the Sun is 1.8 AU, larger than that of any other planet, though not as large as that of <a href=\"/wiki/Dwarf_planet\">dwarf planet</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Pluto\">Pluto</a>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-AA-53\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 47;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[47]</span></a></span> The intensity of sunlight varies inversely with the square of distance, and so on Uranus (at about 20 times the distance from the Sun compared to Earth) it is about 1/400 the intensity of light on Earth.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-54\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 48;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[48]</span></a></span> Its orbital elements were first calculated in 1783 by <a href=\"/wiki/Pierre-Simon_Laplace\">Pierre-Simon Laplace</a>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-georgeforbes-55\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 49;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[49]</span></a></span> With time, discrepancies began to appear between the predicted and observed orbits, and in 1841, <a href=\"/wiki/John_Couch_Adams\">John Couch Adams</a> first proposed that the differences might be due to the gravitational tug of an unseen planet. In 1845, <a href=\"/wiki/Urbain_Le_Verrier\">Urbain Le Verrier</a> began his own independent research into Uranus's orbit. On September 23, 1846, <a href=\"/wiki/Johann_Gottfried_Galle\">Johann Gottfried Galle</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Discovery_of_Neptune\">located a new planet</a>, later named <a href=\"/wiki/Neptune\">Neptune</a>, at nearly the position predicted by Le Verrier.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-56\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 50;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[50]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>The rotational period of the interior of Uranus is 17<span>&nbsp;</span>hours, 14<span>&nbsp;</span>minutes. As on all the <a href=\"/wiki/Giant_planet\">giant planets</a>, its upper atmosphere experiences strong winds in the direction of rotation. At some latitudes, such as about 60 degrees south, visible features of the atmosphere move much faster, making a full rotation in as little as 14 hours.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-57\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 51;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[51]</span></a></span></p>\n\n","toclevel":1,"line":"Orbit and rotation","anchor":"Orbit_and_rotation"},{"id":5,"text":"\n\n<p>The Uranian axis of rotation is approximately parallel with the plane of the Solar System, with an <a href=\"/wiki/Axial_tilt\">axial tilt</a> of 97.77 (as defined by prograde rotation). This gives it seasonal changes completely unlike those of the other planets. Near the <a href=\"/wiki/Solstice\">solstice</a>, one pole faces the Sun continuously and the other faces away. Only a narrow strip around the equator experiences a rapid daynight cycle, but with the Sun low over the horizon. At the other side of Uranus's orbit the orientation of the poles towards the Sun is reversed. It is the fourth-largest planet by diameter and the third-largest by mass. Among the <a href=\"/wiki/Giant_planet\">giant planets</a> in the Solar System, Neptune is the most dense. Neptune is 17 times the mass of <a href=\"/wiki/Earth\">Earth</a> and is slightly more massive than its near-twin <a href=\"/wiki/Uranus\">Uranus</a>, which is 15 times the mass of Earth and slightly larger than Neptune.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-mass2-12\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 3;\" data-mw-group=\"lower-alpha\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[lower-alpha 3]</span></a></span> Neptune orbits the Sun once every 164.8<span>&nbsp;</span><a href=\"/wiki/Julian_year_(astronomy)\">years</a> at an average distance of <span>30.1 </span><a href=\"/wiki/Astronomical_unit\">astronomical unit</a><span>s (4.50</span><span style=\"margin:0 .15em 0 .25em\"></span><span>10</span><sup about=\"#mwt46\">9</sup><span>&nbsp;</span><span>km)</span>. Named after the <a href=\"/wiki/Neptune_(mythology)\">Roman god of the sea</a>, its <a href=\"/wiki/Astronomical_symbol\">astronomical symbol</a> is , a stylised version of the god Neptune's <a href=\"/wiki/Trident\">trident</a>.</p></span><div class=\"hatnote\">This article is about the planet. Unexpected changes in the orbit of Uranus led <a href=\"/wiki/Alexis_Bouvard\">Alexis Bouvard</a> to deduce that its orbit was subject to <a href=\"/wiki/Gravitation\">gravitational</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Perturbation_(astronomy)\">perturbation</a> by an unknown planet. Neptune was subsequently observed with a telescope on 23<span>&nbsp;</span>September 1846<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Hamilton-1\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 1;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[1]</span></a></span> by <a href=\"/wiki/Johann_Galle\">Johann Galle</a> within a <a href=\"/wiki/Degree_(angle)\">degree</a> of the position predicted by <a href=\"/wiki/Urbain_Le_Verrier\">Urbain Le Verrier</a>. Its largest moon, <a href=\"/wiki/Triton_(moon)\">Triton</a>, was discovered shortly thereafter, though none of the planet's remaining known 14 <a href=\"/wiki/Moons_of_Neptune\">moons</a> were located telescopically until the 20th century. The planet's distance from Earth gives it a very small apparent size, making it challenging to study with Earth-based telescopes. Neptune was visited by <i><a href=\"/wiki/Voyager_2\">Voyager 2</a></i>, when it flew by the planet on 25<span>&nbsp;</span>August 1989.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-NYT-20141018-KC-13\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 10;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[10]</span></a></span> The advent of <a href=\"/wiki/Hubble_Space_Telescope\">Hubble Space Telescope</a> and large <a href=\"/wiki/Ground-based_telescope\">ground-based telescopes</a> with <a href=\"/wiki/Adaptive_optics\">adaptive optics</a> has recently allowed for additional detailed observations from afar.</p>\n\n<p>Neptune is similar in composition to Uranus, and both have compositions that differ from those of the larger <a href=\"/wiki/Gas_giant\">gas giants</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Jupiter\">Jupiter</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Saturn\">Saturn</a>. Like Jupiter and Saturn, Neptune's atmosphere is composed primarily of <a href=\"/wiki/Hydrogen\">hydrogen</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Helium\">helium</a>, along with traces of <a href=\"/wiki/Hydrocarbon\">hydrocarbons</a> and possibly <a href=\"/wiki/Nitrogen\">nitrogen</a>, but contains a higher proportion of \"ices\" such as water, <a href=\"/wiki/Ammonia\">ammonia</a>, and <a href=\"/wiki/Methane\">methane</a>. However, its interior, like that of Uranus, is primarily composed of ices and rock,<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Podolak_Weizman_et_al._1995-14\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 11;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[11]</span></a></span> and hence Uranus and Neptune are normally considered \"<a href=\"/wiki/Ice_giant\">ice giants</a>\" to emphasise this distinction.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Lunine_1993-15\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 12;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[12]</span></a></span> Traces of methane in the outermost regions in part account for the planet's blue appearance.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-bluecolour-16\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 13;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[13]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>In contrast to the hazy, relatively featureless atmosphere of Uranus, Neptune's atmosphere has active and visible weather patterns. For example, at the time of the <i>Voyager 2</i> <a href=\"/wiki/Planetary_flyby\">flyby</a> in 1989, the planet's southern hemisphere had a <a href=\"/wiki/Great_Dark_Spot\">Great Dark Spot</a> comparable to the <a href=\"/wiki/Great_Red_Spot\">Great Red Spot</a> on Jupiter. On both occasions, Galileo seems to have mistaken Neptune for a <a href=\"/wiki/Fixed_star\">fixed star</a> when it appeared closein <a href=\"/wiki/Conjunction_(astronomy_and_astrology)\">conjunction</a>to Jupiter in the <a href=\"/wiki/Night_sky\">night sky</a>;<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-21\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 18;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[18]</span></a></span> hence, he is not credited with Neptune's discovery. At his first observation in December 1612, Neptune was almost stationary in the sky because it had just turned <a href=\"/wiki/Apparent_retrograde_motion\">retrograde</a> that day. This apparent backward motion is created when Earth's orbit takes it past an outer planet. Because Neptune was only beginning its yearly retrograde cycle, the motion of the planet was far too slight to be detected with Galileo's small <a href=\"/wiki/Telescope\">telescope</a>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-22\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 19;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[19]</span></a></span> In July 2009, <a href=\"/wiki/University_of_Melbourne\">University of Melbourne</a> physicist David Jamieson announced new evidence suggesting that Galileo was at least aware that the 'star' he had observed had moved relative to the <a href=\"/wiki/Fixed_stars\">fixed stars</a>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-23\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 20;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[20]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>In 1821, <a href=\"/wiki/Alexis_Bouvard\">Alexis Bouvard</a> published astronomical tables of the <a href=\"/wiki/Orbit\">orbit</a> of Neptune's neighbour Uranus.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-24\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 21;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[21]</span></a></span> Subsequent observations revealed substantial deviations from the tables, leading Bouvard to hypothesise that an unknown body was <a href=\"/wiki/Perturbation_(astronomy)\">perturbing</a> the orbit through <a href=\"/wiki/Gravitation\">gravitational</a> interaction.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-MNRAS7-25\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 22;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[22]</span></a></span> In 1843, <a href=\"/wiki/John_Couch_Adams\">John Couch Adams</a> began work on the orbit of Uranus using the data he had. Via <a href=\"/wiki/Cambridge_Observatory\">Cambridge Observatory</a> director <a href=\"/wiki/James_Challis\">James Challis</a>, he requested extra data from Sir <a href=\"/wiki/George_Biddell_Airy\">George Airy</a>, the <a href=\"/wiki/Astronomer_Royal\">Astronomer Royal</a>, who supplied it in February 1844. Adams continued to work in 184546 and produced several different estimates of a new planet.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-26\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 23;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[23]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-27\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 24;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[24]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<figure class=\"mw-default-size mw-halign-left\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Urbain_Le_Verrier.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/89/Urbain_Le_Verrier.jpg/170px-Urbain_Le_Verrier.jpg\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/89/Urbain_Le_Verrier.jpg/340px-Urbain_Le_Verrier.jpg 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/89/Urbain_Le_Verrier.jpg/255px-Urbain_Le_Verrier.jpg 1.5x\" heigh
05-23 18:39:28.048 debug OkHttp t=\"216\" width=\"170\"></a><figcaption><a href=\"/wiki/Urbain_Le_Verrier\" class=\"image\">Urbain Le Verrier</a></figcaption></figure>\n\n<p>In 184546, <a href=\"/wiki/Urbain_Le_Verrier\">Urbain Le Verrier</a>, independently of Adams, developed his own calculations but aroused no enthusiasm in his compatriots. In June 1846, upon seeing Le Verrier's first published estimate of the planet's longitude and its similarity to Adams's estimate, Airy persuaded Challis to search for the planet. Challis vainly scoured the sky throughout August and September.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-MNRAS7-25\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 22;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[22]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-28\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 25;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[25]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>Meanwhile, Le Verrier by letter urged <a href=\"/wiki/Berlin_Observatory\">Berlin Observatory</a> astronomer <a href=\"/wiki/Johann_Gottfried_Galle\">Johann Gottfried Galle</a> to search with the observatory's <a href=\"/wiki/Refractor\">refractor</a>. <a href=\"/wiki/Heinrich_Louis_d'Arrest\">Heinrich d'Arrest</a>, a student at the observatory, suggested to Galle that they could compare a recently drawn chart of the sky in the region of Le Verrier's predicted location with the current sky to seek the displacement characteristic of a <a href=\"/wiki/Planet\">planet</a>, as opposed to a fixed star. On the evening of 23<span>&nbsp;</span>September 1846, the day Galle received the letter, he discovered Neptune within 1 of where Le Verrier had predicted it to be, about 12 from Adams' prediction. Challis later realised that he had observed the planet twice, on 4 and 12<span>&nbsp;</span>August, but did not recognise it as a planet because he lacked an up-to-date star map and was distracted by his concurrent work on comet observations.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-MNRAS7-25\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 22;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[22]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-29\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 26;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[26]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>In the wake of the discovery, there was much nationalistic rivalry between the French and the British over who deserved credit for the discovery. Eventually, an international consensus emerged that both Le Verrier and Adams jointly deserved credit. Since 1966, <a href=\"/wiki/Dennis_Rawlins\">Dennis Rawlins</a> has questioned the credibility of Adams's claim to co-discovery, and the issue was re-evaluated by historians with the return in 1998 of the \"Neptune papers\" (historical documents) to the <a href=\"/wiki/Royal_Observatory,_Greenwich\">Royal Observatory, Greenwich</a>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Neptdisc-30\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 27;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[27]</span></a></span> After reviewing the documents, they suggest that \"Adams does not deserve equal credit with Le Verrier for the discovery of Neptune. That credit belongs only to the person who succeeded both in predicting the planet's place and in convincing astronomers to search for it.\"<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-31\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 28;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[28]</span></a></span></p>\n\n","toclevel":2,"line":"Discovery","anchor":"Discovery"},{"id":3,"text":"\n<p>Shortly after its discovery, Neptune was referred to simply as \"the planet exterior to Uranus\" or as \"Le Verrier's planet\". The first suggestion for a name came from Galle, who proposed the name <i><a href=\"/wiki/Janus_(mythology)\">Janus</a></i>. In England, Challis put forward the name <i><a href=\"/wiki/Oceanus\">Oceanus</a></i>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-32\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 29;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[29]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>Claiming the right to name his discovery, Le Verrier quickly proposed the name <i>Neptu
05-23 18:39:28.108 debug OkHttp ne</i> for this new planet, though falsely stating that this had been officially approved by the French <a href=\"/wiki/Bureau_des_Longitudes\">Bureau des Longitudes</a>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-33\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 30;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[30]</span></a></span> In October, he sought to name the planet <i>Le Verrier</i>, after himself, and he had loyal support in this from the observatory director, <a href=\"/wiki/Franois_Arago\">Franois Arago</a>. This suggestion met with stiff resistance outside France.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-34\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 31;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[31]</span></a></span> French almanacs quickly reintroduced the name <i>Herschel</i> for <i>Uranus</i>, after that planet's discoverer Sir <a href=\"/wiki/William_Herschel\">William Herschel</a>, and <i>Leverrier</i> for the new planet.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-35\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 32;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[32]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p><a href=\"/wiki/Friedrich_Georg_Wilhelm_von_Struve\">Struve</a> came out in favour of the name <i>Neptune</i> on 29<span>&nbsp;</span>December 1846, to the <a href=\"/wiki/Russian_Academy_of_Sciences\">Saint Petersburg Academy of Sciences</a>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-36\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 33;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[33]</span></a></span> Soon, <i>Neptune</i> became the internationally accepted name. In <a href=\"/wiki/Roman_mythology\">Roman mythology</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Neptune_(mythology)\">Neptune</a> was the god of the sea, identified with the Greek <a href=\"/wiki/Poseidon\">Poseidon</a>. The demand for a mythological name seemed to be in keeping with the nomenclature of the other planets, all of which, except for Earth, were named for deities in <a href=\"/wiki/Greek_mythology\">Greek</a> and Roman mythology.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-USGS-37\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 34;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[34]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>Most languages today, even in countries that have no direct link to Greco-Roman culture, use some variant of the name \"Neptune\" for the planet. However, in Chinese, Japanese, and <a href=\"/wiki/Korean_language\">Korean</a>, the planet's name was translated as \"sea king star\" (<span></span>), because Neptune was the god of the sea.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-38\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 35;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[35]</span></a></span> In <a href=\"/wiki/Mongolian_language\">Mongolian</a>, Neptune is called <i>Dalain Van</i> ( ), reflecting its namesake god's role as the ruler of the sea. In modern <a href=\"/wiki/Greek_language\">Greek</a> the planet is called <i>Poseidon</i> (, <i>Poseidonas</i>), the Greek counterpart of Neptune.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-39\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 36;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[36]</span></a></span> In <a href=\"/wiki/Hebrew_language\">Hebrew</a>, \"Rahab\" (), from <a href=\"/wiki/Rahab_(Egypt)#Jewish_folklore\">a Biblical sea monster</a> mentioned in the <a href=\"/wiki/Book_of_Psalms\">Book of Psalms</a>, was selected in a vote managed by the <a href=\"/wiki/Academy_of_the_Hebrew_Language\">Academy of the Hebrew Language</a> in 2009 as the official name for the planet, even though the existing Latin term \"Neptun\" () is commonly used.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Haaretz-40\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 37;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[37]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Hayadan.org.il-41\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 38;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[38]</span></a></span> In <a href=\"/wiki/Mori_language\">Mori</a>, the planet is called <i>Tangaroa</i>, named after the <a href=\"/wiki/Tangaroa\">Mori god of the sea</a>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-42\" style=\"count
05-23 18:39:28.108 debug OkHttp er-reset: mw-Ref 39;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[39]</span></a></span> In <a href=\"/wiki/Nahuatl_language\">Nahuatl</a>, the planet is called <i>Tllocctlalli</i>, named after the rain god <a href=\"/wiki/Tlaloc\">Tlloc</a>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-43\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 40;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[40]</span></a></span></p>\n\n","toclevel":2,"line":"Naming","anchor":"Naming"},{"id":4,"text":"\n<p>From its discovery in 1846 until the subsequent <a href=\"/wiki/Discovery_of_Pluto\">discovery of Pluto</a> in 1930, Neptune was the farthest known planet. When Pluto was discovered it was considered a planet, and Neptune thus became the penultimate known planet, except for a 20-year period between 1979 and 1999 when Pluto's elliptical orbit brought it closer to the Sun than Neptune.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-44\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 41;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[41]</span></a></span> The discovery of the <a href=\"/wiki/Kuiper_belt\">Kuiper belt</a> in 1992 led many astronomers to debate whether Pluto should be considered a planet or as part of the Kuiper belt.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-45\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 42;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[42]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-46\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 43;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[43]</span></a></span> In 2006, the <a href=\"/wiki/International_Astronomical_Union\">International Astronomical Union</a> <a href=\"/wiki/2006_definition_of_planet\">defined the word \"planet\" for the first time</a>, reclassifying Pluto as a \"<a href=\"/wiki/Dwarf_planet\">dwarf planet</a>\" and making Neptune once again the outermost known planet in the Solar System.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-47\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 44;\"><span He is the <a href=\"/wiki/List_of_African-American_firsts\">first</a> <a href=\"/wiki/African_American\">African American</a> to hold the office, as well as the first president born outside of the <a href=\"/wiki/Contiguous_United_States\">continental United States</a>. Born in <a href=\"/wiki/Honolulu\">Honolulu</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Hawaii\">Hawaii</a>, Obama is a graduate of <a href=\"/wiki/Columbia_University\">Columbia University</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Harvard_Law_School\">Harvard Law School</a>, where he served as president of the <i><a href=\"/wiki/Harvard_Law_Review\">Harvard Law Review</a></i>. He was a <a href=\"/wiki/Community_organizing\">community organizer</a> in <a href=\"/wiki/Chicago\">Chicago</a> before earning his <a href=\"/wiki/Juris_Doctor\">law degree</a>. He worked as a <a href=\"/wiki/Civil_and_political_rights\">civil rights</a> attorney and taught <a href=\"/wiki/Constitutional_law\">constitutional law</a> at <a href=\"/wiki/University_of_Chicago_Law_School\">University of Chicago Law School</a> between 1992 and 2004. He began his presidential campaign in 2007 and, after <a href=\"/wiki/Barack_Obama_presidential_primary_campaign,_2008\">a close primary campaign</a> against <a href=\"/wiki/Hillary_Clinton\">Hillary Rodham Clinton</a> in 2008, he won sufficient delegates in the <a href=\"/wiki/Democratic_Party_presidential_primaries,_2008\">Democratic Party p

He then defeated <a href=\"/wiki/Republican_Party_(United_States)\">Republican</a> nominee <a href=\"/wiki/John_McCain\">John McCain</a> in the <a href=\"/wiki/United_States_presidential_election,_2008\">general election</a>, and was <a href=\"/wiki/First_inauguration_of_Barack_Obama\">inaugurated as president</a> on January 20, 2009. Nine months after his inauguration, Obama was named the <a href=\"/wiki/2009_Nobel_Peace_Prize\">2009 Nobel Peace Prize</a> laureate.</p>\n\n<p>During his first two years in office, Obama signed into law <a href=\"/wiki/Stimulus_(economics)\">economic stimulus</a> legislation in response to the <a href=\"/wiki/Great_Recession\">Great Recession</a> in the form of the <a href=\"/wiki/American_Recovery_and_Reinvestment_Act_of_2009\">American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009</a> and the <a href=\"/wiki/Tax_Relief,_Unemployment_Insurance_Reauthorization,_and_Job_Creation_Act_of_2010\">Tax Relief, Unemployment Insurance Reauthorization, and Job Creation Act of 2010</a>. Other major domestic initiatives in his first term included the <a href=\"/wiki/Patient_Protection_and_Affordable_Care_Act\">Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act</a>, often referred to as \"Obamacare\"; the <a href=\"/wiki/DoddFrank_Wall_Street_Reform_and_Consumer_Protection_Act\">DoddFrank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act</a>; and the <a href=\"/wiki/Don't_Ask,_Don't_Tell_Repeal_Act_of_2010\">Don't Ask, Don't Tell Repeal Act of 2010</a>. In foreign policy, Obama <a href=\"/wiki/Withdrawal_of_U.S._troops_from_Iraq\">ended U.S. military involvement</a> in the <a href=\"/wiki/Iraq_War\">Iraq War</a>, increased U.S. troop levels in <a href=\"/wiki/War_in_Afghanistan_(2001present)\">Afghanistan</a>, signed the <a href=\"/wiki/New_START\">New START</a> arms control treaty with <a href=\"/wiki/Russia\">Russia</a>, ordered <a href=\"/wiki/2011_military_intervention_in_Libya\">U.S. military involvement in Libya</a> in opposition to <a href=\"/wiki/Muammar_Gaddafi\">Muammar Gaddafi</a>, and ordered the military operation that resulted in the <a href=\"/wiki/Death_of_Osama_bin_Laden\">death of Osama bin Laden</a>. In January 2011, <a href=\"/wiki/United_States_midterm_elections,_2010\">the Republicans regained control of the House of Representatives</a> as the Democratic Party lost a total of 63 seats; and, after a lengthy debate over federal spending and whether or not to raise the nation's <a href=\"/wiki/United_States_debt_ceiling\">debt limit</a>, Obama signed the <a href=\"/wiki/Budget_Control_Act_of_2011\">Budget Control Act of 2011</a> and the <a href=\"/wiki/American_Taxpayer_Relief_Act_of_2012\">American Taxpayer Relief Act of 2012</a>.</p>\n\n<p>Obama was <a href=\"/wiki/United_States_presidential_election,_2012\">reelected president</a> in November 2012, defeating Republican nominee <a href=\"/wiki/Mitt_Romney\">Mitt Romney</a>, and was <a href=\"/wiki/Second_inauguration_of_Barack_Obama\">sworn in for a second term</a> on January 20, 2013. During his second term, Obama has promoted domestic policies related to <a href=\"/wiki/Gun_politics_in_the_United_States\">gun control</a> in response to the <a href=\"/wiki/Sandy_Hook_Elementary_School_shooting\">Sandy Hook Elementary School shooting</a>, and has called for greater inclusiveness for <a href=\"/wiki/LGBT_Americans\">LGBT Americans</a>, while his administration has filed briefs which urged the <a href=\"/wiki/Supreme_Court_of_the_United_States\">Supreme Court</a> to strike down part of the federal <a href=\"/wiki/Defense_of_Marriage_Act\">Defense of Marriage Act</a> and state level <a href=\"/wiki/Same-sex_marriage_in_the_United_States\">same-sex marriage</a> bans as unconstitutional. In foreign policy, Obama ordered <a href=\"/wiki/American-led_intervention_in_Iraq_(2014present)\">U.S. military intervention in Iraq</a> in response to <a href=\"/wiki/Iraqi_insurgency_(2011present)\">gains made</a> by

There are several hypotheses for its origin; the most widely accepted explanation is that the Moon formed from the debris left over after a <a href=\"/wiki/Giant_impact_hypothesis\">giant impact</a> between Earth and a <a href=\"/wiki/Mars\">Mars</a>-sized body called <a href=\"/wiki/Theia_(planet)\">Theia</a>.</p>\n\n<p>The Moon is in <a href=\"/wiki/Synchronous_rotation\">synchronous rotation</a> with Earth, always showing the same face with its <a href=\"/wiki/Near_side_of_the_Moon\">near side</a> marked by dark volcanic <a href=\"/wiki/Lunar_mare\">maria</a> that fill between the bright ancient crustal highlands and the prominent <a href=\"/wiki/Impact_crater\">impact craters</a>. It is the second-brightest regularly visible <a href=\"/wiki/Celestial_object\">celestial object</a> in Earth's sky after the <a href=\"/wiki/Sun\">Sun</a>, as measured by <a href=\"/wiki/Illuminance\">illuminance</a> on Earth's surface. Its surface is actually dark (although it can appear a <a href=\"/wiki/Moonlight\">very bright white</a>) with a <a href=\"/wiki/Reflectance\">reflectance</a> just slightly higher than that of worn <a href=\"/wiki/Asphalt_concrete\">asphalt</a>. Its prominence in the sky and its regular cycle of <a href=\"/wiki/Lunar_phases\">phases</a> have made the Moon an important <a href=\"/wiki/Culture\">cultural</a> influence since <a href=\"/wiki/Ancient_history\">ancient</a> times on <a href=\"/wiki/Moon#Name_and_etymology\">language</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Lunar_calendar\">calendars</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Moon_in_fiction\">art</a>, and <a href=\"/wiki/Lunar_deity\">mythology</a>.</p>\n\n<p>The Moon's gravitational influence produces the <a href=\"/wiki/Ocean_tides\">ocean tides</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Earth_tide\">body tides</a>, and the <a href=\"/wiki/Tidal_acceleration\">slight lengthening</a> of the day. The Moon's current orbital distance is about thirty times the diameter of Earth, with its <a href=\"/wiki/Angular_diameter\">apparent size</a> in the sky almost the same as that of the Sun, resulting in th
05-23 18:39:44.650 debug OkHttp e Moon covering the Sun nearly precisely in total <a href=\"/wiki/Solar_eclipse\">solar eclipse</a>. This matching of apparent visual size will not continue in the far future. The Moon's linear distance from Earth is currently increasing at a rate of <span>3.82</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span></span><span>&nbsp;</span><span>0.07 centimetres (1.504</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span></span><span>&nbsp;</span><span>0.028</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span>in)</span> per year, but this rate is not constant.</p>\n\n<p>The <a href=\"/wiki/Soviet_Union\">Soviet Union</a>'s <a href=\"/wiki/Luna_programme\">Luna programme</a> was the first to reach the Moon with <a href=\"/wiki/Unmanned_spacecraft\">unmanned spacecraft</a> in 1959; the <a href=\"/wiki/United_States\">United States</a>' <a href=\"/wiki/NASA\">NASA</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Apollo_program\">Apollo program</a> achieved the only manned missions to date, beginning with the first manned lunar orbiting mission by <a href=\"/wiki/Apollo_8\">Apollo 8</a> in 1968, and six manned lunar landings between 1969 and 1972, with the first being <a href=\"/wiki/Apollo_11\">Apollo 11</a>. These missions returned over <span>380</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span>kg (840</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span>lb)</span> of <a href=\"/wiki/Moon_rock\">lunar rocks</a>, which have been used to develop a <a href=\"/wiki/Geology\">geological</a> understanding of the Moon's origin, the formation of <a href=\"/wiki/Internal_structure_of_the_Moon\">its internal structure</a>, and <a href=\"/wiki/Geology_of_the_Moon\">its subsequent history</a>. After the <a href=\"/wiki/Apollo_17\">Apollo 17</a> mission in 1972, the Moon has been visited only by unmanned spacecraft.</p>\n\n"},{"id":1,"toclevel":1,"anchor":"Name_and_etymology","line":"Name class=\"hatnote\">See also: <a href=\"/wiki/List_of_lunar_deities\">list of lunar deities</a></div>\n\n<p>The usual English <a href=\"/wiki/Proper_name\">proper name</a> for Earth's natural satellite is \"the Moon\".<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-15\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 10;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[10]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-PN-FAQ-16\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 11;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[11]</span></a></span> The noun <i>moon</i> is derived from <i>moone</i> (around 1380), which developed from <i>mone</i> (1135), which is derived from <a href=\"/wiki/Old_English\">Old English</a> <i>mna</i> (dating from before 725), which ultimately stems from <a href=\"/wiki/Proto-Germanic\">Proto-Germanic</a> <i>*mnn</i>, like all <a href=\"/wiki/Germanic_languages\">Germanic language</a> cognates.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-barnhart1995-17\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 12;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[12]</span></a></span> Occasionally, the name \"Luna\" is used, such as for a personified Moon in poetry or to distinguish it from other moons in science fiction.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-18\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 13;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[13]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>The principal modern English adjective pertaining to the Moon is <i>lunar</i>, derived from the Latin <i>Luna</i>. A less common adjective is <i>selenic</i>, derived from the Ancient Greek <i><a href=\"/wiki/Selene\">Selene</a></i> (<span><i></i></span>), from which is derived the prefix \"seleno-\" (as in <i><a href=\"/wiki/Selenography\">selenography</a></i>).<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-oed-19\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 14;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[14]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-20\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 15;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[15]</span></a></span> Both the Greek Selene and the Roman goddess <a href=\"/wiki/Diana_(mythology)\">Diana</a> were alternatively called <a href=\"/wiki/Cynthia\">Cynthia</a>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Pannen2010-21\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 16;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[16]</span></a></span> The names Luna, Cynthia, and Selene are reflected in terminology for <a href=\"/wiki/Lunar_orbit\">lunar orbits</a> in words such as <i>apolune</i>, <i>pericynthion</i>, and <i>selenocentric</i>. 05-23 18:39:45.668 debug OkHttp /European_Space_Agency\">European Space Agency</a> each sent lunar orbiters, especially <a href=\"/wiki/ISRO\">ISRO</a>'s <i><a href=\"/wiki/Chandrayaan-1\">Chandrayaan-1</a></i> has contributed to confirming the discovery of <a href=\"/wiki/Lunar_water\">lunar water ice</a> in permanently shadowed craters at the poles and bound into the lunar <a href=\"/wiki/Regolith\">regolith</a>. The post-Apollo era has also seen two <a href=\"/wiki/Rover_(space_exploration)\">rover</a> missions: the final Soviet <a href=\"/wiki/Lunokhod\">Lunokhod</a> mission in 1973, and China's ongoing <a href=\"/wiki/Chang'e_3\">Chang'e 3</a> mission, which deployed its <a href=\"/wiki/Yutu_(rover)\">Yutu rover</a> on 14 December 2013. The Moon remains, under the <a href=\"/wiki/Outer_Space_Treaty\">Outer Space Treaty</a>, free to all nations to explore for peaceful purposes.</p>\n\n","toclevel":4,"line":"1980s2000","anchor":"1980s.E2.80.932000"},{"id":28,"text":"\n\n<p>The European spacecraft <i><a href=\"/wiki/SMART-1\">SMART-1</a></i>, the second <a href=\"/wiki/Ion_propulsion\">ion-propelled</a> spacecraft, was in lunar orbit from 15 November 2004 until its lunar impact on 3 September 2006, and made the first detailed survey of chemical elements on the lunar surface.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-194\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 181;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[181]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>China has pursued an ambitious <a href=\"/wiki/Chinese_Lunar_Exploration_Program\">program of lunar exploration</a>, beginning with <i><a href=\"/wiki/Chang'e_1\">Chang'e 1</a></i>, which successfully orbited the Moon from 5 November 2007 until its controlled lunar impact on 1 March 2009.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-xinhua_20090301-195\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 182;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[182]</span></a></span> In its sixteen-month mission, it obtained a full image map of the Moon. China followed up this success with <i><a href=\"/wiki/Chang'e_2\">Chang'e 2</a></i> beginning in October 2010, which reached the Moon over twice as fast as <i>Chang'e 1</i>, mapped the Moon at a higher resolution over an eight-month period, then left lunar orbit in favor of an extended stay at the EarthSun L2 <a href=\"/wiki/Lagrangian_point\">Lagrangian point</a>, before finally performing a flyby of asteroid <a href=\"/wiki/4179_Toutatis\">4179 Toutatis</a> on 13 December 2012, and then heading off into deep space. On 14 December 2013, <i><a href=\"/wiki/Chang'e_3\">Chang'e 3</a></i> improved upon its orbital mission predecessors by landing a lunar <a href=\"/wiki/Lander_(spacecraft)\">lander</a> onto the Moon's surface, which in turn deployed a <a href=\"/wiki/Lunar_rover\">lunar rover</a>, named <i>Yutu</i> (Chinese: ; literally \"Jade Rabbit\"). In so doing, <i>Chang'e 3</i> made the first lunar <a href=\"/wiki/Soft_landing_(rocketry)\">soft landing</a> since <i><a href=\"/wiki/Luna_24\">Luna 24</a></i> in 1976, and the first lunar rover mission since <i><a href=\"/wiki/Lunokhod_2\">Lunokhod 2</a></i> in 1973. China intends to launch another rover mission (<i><a href=\"/wiki/Chang'e_4\">Chang'e 4</a></i>) in 2015, followed by a <a href=\"/wiki/Sample_return_mission\">sample return mission</a> (<i><a href=\"/wiki/Chang'e_5\">Chang'e 5</a></i>) in 2017.</p>\n\n<p>Between 4 October 2007 and 10 June 2009, the <a href=\"/wiki/Japan_Aerospace_Exploration_Agency\">Japan Aerospace Exploration Agency</a>'s <i><a href=\"/wiki/SELENE\">Kaguya</a> (Selene)</i> mission, a lunar orbiter fitted with a <a href=\"/wiki/High-definition_video\">high-definition video</a> camera, and two small radio-transmitter satellites, obtained lunar geophysics data and took the first high-definition movies from beyond Earth orbit.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-196\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 183;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[183]</span></a></span><span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-197\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 1

It is a motif in the visual arts, the performing arts, poetry, prose and music. A 5,000-year-old rock carving at <a href=\"/wiki/Knowth\">Knowth</a>, Ireland, may represent the Moon, which would be the earliest depiction discovered.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-spacetoday-239\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 226;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[226]</span></a></span> The contrast between the brighter highlands and the darker maria creates the patterns seen by different cultures as the <a href=\"/wiki/Man_in_the_Moon\">Man in the Moon</a>, the <a href=\"/wiki/Moon_rabbit\">rabbit</a> and the buffalo, among others. In many prehistoric and ancient cultures, the Moon was personified as <a href=\"/wiki/Lunar_deity\">a deity</a> or other <a href=\"/wiki/Supernatural\">supernatural</a> phenomenon, and <a href=\"/wiki/Moon_(astrology)\">astrological views of the Moon</a> continue to be propagated today.</p>\n\n<p>The Moon plays an important role in <a href=\"/wiki/Islam\">Islam</a>; the <a href=\"/wiki/Islamic_calendar\">Islamic calendar</a> is strictly lunar, and in many Muslim countries the months are determined by the visual sighting of the <a href=\"/wiki/Hilal_(crescent_moon)\">hilal</a>, or earliest crescent moon, over the horizon.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-240\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 227;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[227]</span></a></span> The <a href=\"/wiki/Splitting_of_the_moon\">splitting of the moon</a> (<a href=\"/wiki/Arabic_language\">Arabic</a><span>:</span><span> </span><span dir=\"rtl\"> </span><span></span>) was a miracle attributed to <a href=\"/wiki/Muhammad\">Muhammad</a>.<span class=\"mw-ref\"><a href=\"#cite_note-241\" style=\"counter-reset: mw-Ref 228;\"><span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[228]</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p>The Moon has long been associated with insanity and irrationality; the words <i>lunacy</i> and <i><a href=\"/wiki/Lunatic\">lunatic</a></i> (popular shortening <i>loony</i>) are derived from the Latin name for the Moon, <i>Luna</i>. Philosophers <a href=\"/wiki/Aristotle\">Aristotle</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Pliny_the_Elder\">Pliny the Elder</a> argued that the full moon induced insanity in susceptible individuals, believing that the brain, which is mostly water, must be affected by the Moon and its power over the tides, but the Moon's gravity is too slight to affect any single person.<span cl
